{"title_page": "Coroebus of Elis", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Coroebus of Elis\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Elis]]\n| alma_mater = \n| headercolor = \n| show-medals = yes\n| event = [[Stadion (running race)|Stadion]]\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | [[Ancient Greek Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | [[Elis]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | 776 BC Olympia | [[Stadion (running race)|Stadion]]}}\n}}\n[[File:Panathenaic amphora Kleophrades Louvre F277.jpg|thumb|Runners (ca. 500 B.C.E.)]]\n'''Coroebus of Elis''', commonly spelled '''Koroibos''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u039a\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03b9\u03b2\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f28\u03bb\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2), was a Greek cook,<ref>Michael Symons, ''A History of Cooks and Cooking'', University of Illinois Press, 2003, p.300</ref> baker<ref>Robert Garland. ''Celebrity in Antiquity: From Media Tarts to Tabloid Queens''. London: Duckworth, 2006.</ref> and athlete from [[Elis]], who won the [[Stadion (running race)|stadion]] race in the first recorded [[Ancient Olympic Games]] in 776 BC.\n\n==Olympics==\nThe ''[[Stadion (running race)|stadion]]'' race of the [[Ancient Greece|Greeks]] seem to have been accurately recorded. The prize he received was an olive branch, though the honor of winning was far more prestigious than the actual prize.<ref>[[Eusebius]]. ''[[Chronicon (Eusebius)|Chronicon]]'' ([http://www.attalus.org/translate/eusebius2.html English translation from Latin, original Greek lost]) at Attalus.org</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ancient Olympic winners}}\n{{Ancient Greece topics}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:Ancient Olympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Ancient Eleans]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek runners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Coroebus of Elis\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Elis]]\n| alma_mater = \n| headercolor = \n| show-medals = yes\n| event = [[Stadion (running race)|Stadion]]\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | [[Ancient Greek Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | [[Elis]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold  | 776 BC Olympia | [[Stadion (running race)|Stadion]]}}\n}}\n[[File:Panathenaic amphora Kleophrades Louvre F277.jpg|thumb|Runners (ca. 500 BC)]]\n'''Coroebus of Elis''', commonly spelled '''Koroibos''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u039a\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03b9\u03b2\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f28\u03bb\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2), was a Greek cook,<ref>Michael Symons, ''A History of Cooks and Cooking'', University of Illinois Press, 2003, p.300</ref> baker<ref>Robert Garland. ''Celebrity in Antiquity: From Media Tarts to Tabloid Queens''. London: Duckworth, 2006.</ref> and athlete from [[Elis]], who won the [[Stadion (running race)|stadion]] race in the first recorded [[Ancient Olympic Games]] in 776 BC.\n\n==Olympics==\nThe ''[[Stadion (running race)|stadion]]'' race of the [[Ancient Greece|Greeks]] seem to have been accurately recorded. The prize he received was an olive branch, though the honor of winning was far more prestigious than the actual prize.<ref>[[Eusebius]]. ''[[Chronicon (Eusebius)|Chronicon]]'' ([http://www.attalus.org/translate/eusebius2.html English translation from Latin, original Greek lost]) at Attalus.org</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ancient Olympic winners}}\n{{Ancient Greece topics}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century BC Greek people]]\n[[Category:Ancient Olympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Ancient Eleans]]\n[[Category:Ancient Greek runners]]\n", "name_user": "92.9.165.255", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(ca. 500 BC to ca. 500 B.C.E.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coroebus_of_Elis"}
{"title_page": "Action of 17 July 1761", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Action of 17 July 1761\n|partof=the [[Seven Years' War]]\n|image=Ship of 74-gun model 1760.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption=Model of HMS ''Thunderer'' from 1760. [[National Maritime Museum]]\n|date=14&ndash;17 July 1761\n|place=Off [[C\u00e1diz]], [[Atlantic Ocean]]\n|result=British victory\n|combatant1={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n|commander1={{flagdeco|Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}} Charles Proby\n|commander2={{flagdeco|Kingdom of France|naval}} Unknown Captain\n|strength1=2 ships of the line <br> 1 frigate <br> 1 sloop\n|strength2=1 ship of the line <br> 1 frigate\n|casualties1=34 killed<br>96 wounded\n|casualties2=1 ship of the line captured <br> 1 frigate captured\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Seven Years' War: European}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Action of 17 July 1761''' was a naval engagement fought off the Spanish port of [[C\u00e1diz]] between a British [[Royal Navy]] squadron and a smaller [[French Navy]] squadron during the [[Seven Years' War]]. British fleets had achieved dominance in European waters over the French following heavy defeats of French fleets in 1759. To maintain this control, British battle squadrons were stationed off French ports, as well as ports in neutral but French-supporting [[Kingdom of Spain|Spain]] which sheltered French warships. In 1761, two French ships, the 64-gun [[ship of the line]] ''Achille'' and 32-gun [[frigate]] ''Bouffone'' were [[blockade]]d in the principal Spanish naval base of C\u00e1diz, on the Southern Atlantic coast of Spain.\n\n''Achille'' had departed the French Atlantic base of [[Brest, France|Brest]] in March, fighting though the blockade of that port, and was then trapped in C\u00e1diz by a British squadron detached from the Mediterranean Fleet based at [[Gibraltar]] comprising ships of the line [[HMS Thunderer (1760)|HMS ''Thunderer'']] and [[HMS Modeste (1759)|HMS ''Modeste'']], frigate HMS ''Thetis'' and [[sloop]] HMS ''Favourite'', under the command of Captain Charles Proby on ''Thunderer''. When the French ship attempted to leave Proby gave chase, eventually catching them and bringing them to battle. ''Thunderer'' suffered heavy losses when a cannon exploded, but Proby was able to bring his ship alongside ''Achille'' and capture the ship in a [[naval boarding|boarding action]] while ''Thetis'' and ''Modeste'' captured ''Bouffone''.\n\n==Action==\n\n===Background===\nIn 1759 the [[French Navy]] suffered heavy losses in the defeats at the [[Battle of Lagos]] and the [[Battle of Quiberon Bay]], which gave the [[Royal Navy]] superiority in the Atlantic.<ref name=\"WLC232\">Clowes, p.232</ref> To retain this advantage, the Royal Navy stationed squadrons off the principal French naval bases in a strategy of close [[blockade]]; French ships periodically attempted to break through this blockade to operate against British commerce. On 9 March 1761, the squadron off the port of [[Brest, France|Brest]] in [[Brittany]], led by Commodore [[Matthew Buckle]], sighted a French [[ships of the line]] and a [[frigate]] sailing from the port. Buckle ordered the 60-gun British ship [[HMS Rippon (1758)|HMS ''Rippon'']] under Captain Edward Jekyll to pursue the French, Jekyll chasing the enemy ships into the [[Bay of Biscay]]. The French ships were the 64-gun ''Achille'' and frigate ''Bouffone''.<ref name=\"WLC305\"/>\n\nAlthough the French ships outdistanced ''Rippon'', Jekyll sighted them again the following afternoon and at 21:30 successful drew alongside ''Achille'', opening fire at close range. The wind was strong and the seas rough, neither ship able to easily use their lower gun deck without water sloshing in through the gunports. During the exchange of fire, one of the guns on ''Rippon'' suddenly exploded, causing heavy casualties among the gun crews. Jekyll was forced to order most of the forward gunports closed in consequence, but fire from ''Rippon'' was able to knock away the foreyard and foretop mast on ''Achille''. This caused ''Rippon'' to pull ahead of ''Achille'' and Jekyll brought his ship into the wind in readiness for an attack by the French ship. ''Achille'' however passed by the stern of ''Rippon'' missing the opportunity to [[raking fire|rake]] the British ship. With the French now pulling away, Jekyll ordered his crew to [[Jibe (sailing)|wear around]] and follow ''Achille'', but the damage to the British ship was too extensive and ''Achille'' was able to escape in the darkness.<ref name=\"WLC305\">Clowes, p.305</ref>\n\nHaving escaped the blockade, ''Achille'' and ''Bouffone'' cruised in the Atlantic for several months before entering the neutral but friendly Spanish port of [[C\u00e1diz]]. There they were discovered in July and a small British squadron sent to blockade the harbour in anticipation of ''Achille'' returning to sea.\n\n===Battle===\nThe British blockade squadron stationed off C\u00e1diz comprised the 74-gun [[HMS Thunderer (1760)|HMS ''Thunderer'']] under Captain Charles Proby, the 64-gun HMS ''Modeste'' under Captain [[Robert Boyle Walsingham]], the 32-gun frigate [HMS ''Thetis'' under Captain [[John Moutray]] and the [[sloop]] HMS ''Favourite'' under Commander [[Philemon Pownall]].<ref name=\"WLC305\">Clowes, p.305</ref> This force patrolled off the port in early summer, discovering on 14 July that ''Achille'' and ''Bouffone'' had recently sailed unopposed. Proby ordered his squadron to search for the French ships, discovering them on 16 July approximately {{convert|18|mi|km}} southwest of C\u00e1diz. A chase ensued, with the French sailing northwest into the [[Gulf of C\u00e1diz]]. Proby's ships were faster however and ''Thunderer'' successfully reached ''Achille'' on the morning of 17 July approximately {{convert|57|mi|km}} northwest of C\u00e1diz.<ref name=\"LG1\">{{London Gazette|issue=10132|page=2|date=18 August 1761}}</ref>\n\n''Thunderer'' opened fire on ''Achille'' as the ships came within range, the ships of the line exchanging broadsides. As the action intensified, a [[cannon]] on the upper deck of ''Thunderer'' suddenly burst, the explosion killing and wounding dozens of sailors.<ref name=\"WLC305\"/> In the aftermath of the blast, Proby, who had been wounded in the hand, brought ''Thunderer'' alongside ''Achille'' and led a [[naval boarding|boarding action]] which captured ''Achille''. Nearby, ''Thetis'' successfully brought ''Bouffone'' to action, holding up the French frigate long enough that ''Modeste'' was able to come within range. With his frigate heavily outgunned, the French captain surrendered.<ref name=\"LG1\"/>\n\n===Aftermath===\nProby brought the squadron and its prizes back to [[Gibraltar]], where the wounded were treated in the city's hospitals. British casualties were listed as 17 killed and 114 wounded, all on ''Thunderer'' and most from the gun explosion.<ref name=\"LG1\"/> ''Thunderer'' had also taken severe damage to the masts and rigging from French shot. The only other heavily engaged British ship was ''Thetis'' which had also suffered damage to masts and rigging, but received no casualties. According to Proby's dispatch to the [[Admiralty]], no record of French losses was made in the aftermath of the battle.<ref name=\"LG1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=50em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book\n | last = Clowes\n | first = William Laird\n | authorlink = William Laird Clowes\n | year = 1997\n | origyear= 1900\n | chapter = \n | title = The Royal Navy, A History from the Earliest Times to 1900, Volume III\n | publisher = Chatham Publishing\n | location = London\n | isbn = 1-86176-012-4\n}}\n\n{{coord missing|Atlantic Ocean}}\n\n[[Category:Naval battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1761]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of the Seven Years' War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Action of 17 July 1761\n|partof=the [[Seven Years' War]]\n|image=Ship of 74-gun model 1760.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption=Model of HMS ''Thunderer'' from 1760. [[National Maritime Museum]]\n|date=14&ndash;17 July 1761\n|place=Off [[C\u00e1diz]], [[Atlantic Ocean]]\n|result=British victory\n|combatant1={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n|commander1=Captain [[Charles Proby (Royal Navy officer)|Charles Proby]]\n|commander2=\n|strength1=[[HMS Thunderer (1760)|HMS ''Thunderer'']]<br>[[HMS Modeste (1759)|HMS ''Modeste'']]<br>[[HMS Thetis (1747)|HMS ''Thetis'']]<br>[[HMS Favourite (1757)|HMS ''Favourite'']]\n|strength2=[[French ship Achille (1748)|''Achille'']]<br>[[French frigate Bouffone (1757)|''Bouffone'']]\n|casualties1=34 killed<br>96 wounded\n|casualties2=Heavy,<br>''Achille'' & ''Bouffone captured\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Seven Years' War: European}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Action of 17 July 1761''' was a naval engagement fought off the Spanish port of [[C\u00e1diz]] between a British [[Royal Navy]] squadron and a smaller [[French Navy]] squadron during the [[Seven Years' War]]. British fleets had achieved dominance in European waters over the French following heavy defeats of French fleets in 1759. To maintain this control, British battle squadrons were stationed off French ports, as well as ports in neutral but French-supporting [[Kingdom of Spain|Spain]] which sheltered French warships. In 1761, two French ships, the 64-gun [[ship of the line]] [[French ship Achille (1748)|''Achille'']] and 32-gun [[frigate]] [[French frigate Bouffone (1757)|''Bouffone'']] were [[blockade]]d in the principal Spanish naval base of C\u00e1diz, on the Southern Atlantic coast of Spain.\n\n''Achille'' had departed the French Atlantic base of [[Brest, France|Brest]] in March, fighting though the blockade of that port, and was then trapped in C\u00e1diz by a British squadron detached from the Mediterranean Fleet based at [[Gibraltar]] comprising ships of the line [[HMS Thunderer (1760)|HMS ''Thunderer'']] and [[HMS Modeste (1759)|HMS ''Modeste'']], frigate [[HMS Thetis (1747)|HMS ''Thetis'']] and [[sloop]] [[HMS Favourite (1757)|HMS ''Favourite'']], under the command of Captain [[Charles Proby (Royal Navy officer)|Charles Proby]] on ''Thunderer''. When the French ship attempted to leave Proby gave chase, eventually catching them and bringing them to battle. ''Thunderer'' suffered heavy losses when a cannon exploded, but Proby was able to bring his ship alongside ''Achille'' and capture the ship in a [[naval boarding|boarding action]] while ''Thetis'' and ''Modeste'' captured ''Bouffone''.\n\n==Action==\n\n===Background===\nIn 1759 the [[French Navy]] suffered heavy losses in the defeats at the [[Battle of Lagos]] and the [[Battle of Quiberon Bay]], which gave the [[Royal Navy]] superiority in the Atlantic.<ref name=\"WLC232\">Clowes, p.232</ref> To retain this advantage, the Royal Navy stationed squadrons off the principal French naval bases in a strategy of close [[blockade]]; French ships periodically attempted to break through this blockade to operate against British commerce. On 9 March 1761, the squadron off the port of [[Brest, France|Brest]] in [[Brittany]], led by Commodore [[Matthew Buckle]], sighted a French [[ships of the line]] and a [[frigate]] sailing from the port. Buckle ordered the 60-gun British ship [[HMS Rippon (1758)|HMS ''Rippon'']] under Captain [[Edward Jekyll]] to pursue the French, Jekyll chasing the enemy ships into the [[Bay of Biscay]]. The French ships were the 64-gun [[French ship Achille (1748)|''Achille'']] and frigate [[French frigate Bouffone (1757)|''Bouffone'']].<ref name=\"WLC305\"/>\n\nAlthough the French ships outdistanced ''Rippon'', Jekyll sighted them again the following afternoon and at 21:30 successful drew alongside ''Achille'', opening fire at close range. The wind was strong and the seas rough, neither ship able to easily use their lower gun deck without water sloshing in through the gunports. During the exchange of fire, one of the guns on ''Rippon'' suddenly exploded, causing heavy casualties among the gun crews. Jekyll was forced to order most of the forward gunports closed in consequence, but fire from ''Rippon'' was able to knock away the foreyard and foretop mast on ''Achille''. This caused ''Rippon'' to pull ahead of ''Achille'' and Jekyll brought his ship into the wind in readiness for an attack by the French ship. ''Achille'' however passed by the stern of ''Rippon'' missing the opportunity to [[raking fire|rake]] the British ship. With the French now pulling away, Jekyll ordered his crew to [[Jibe (sailing)|wear around]] and follow ''Achille'', but the damage to the British ship was too extensive and ''Achille'' was able to escape in the darkness.<ref name=\"WLC305\">Clowes, p.305</ref>\n\nHaving escaped the blockade, ''Achille'' and ''Bouffone'' cruised in the Atlantic for several months before entering the neutral but friendly Spanish port of [[C\u00e1diz]]. There they were discovered in July and a small British squadron sent to blockade the harbour in anticipation of ''Achille'' returning to sea.\n\n===Battle===\nThe British blockade squadron stationed off C\u00e1diz comprised the 74-gun [[HMS Thunderer (1760)|HMS ''Thunderer'']] under Captain [[Charles Proby (Royal Navy officer)|Charles Proby]], the 64-gun [[HMS Modeste (1759)|HMS ''Modeste'']] under Captain [[Robert Boyle Walsingham]], the 32-gun frigate [[HMS Thetis (1747)|HMS ''Thetis'']] under Captain [[John Moutray]] and the [[sloop]] [[HMS Favourite (1757)|HMS ''Favourite'']] under Commander [[Philemon Pownall]].<ref name=\"WLC305\">Clowes, p.305</ref> This force patrolled off the port in early summer, discovering on 14 July that ''Achille'' and ''Bouffone'' had recently sailed unopposed. Proby ordered his squadron to search for the French ships, discovering them on 16 July approximately {{convert|18|mi|km}} southwest of C\u00e1diz. A chase ensued, with the French sailing northwest into the [[Gulf of C\u00e1diz]]. Proby's ships were faster however and ''Thunderer'' successfully reached ''Achille'' on the morning of 17 July approximately {{convert|57|mi|km}} northwest of C\u00e1diz.<ref name=\"LG1\">{{London Gazette|issue=10132|page=2|date=18 August 1761}}</ref>\n\n''Thunderer'' opened fire on ''Achille'' as the ships came within range, the ships of the line exchanging broadsides. As the action intensified, a [[cannon]] on the upper deck of ''Thunderer'' suddenly burst, the explosion killing and wounding dozens of sailors.<ref name=\"WLC305\"/> In the aftermath of the blast, Proby, who had been wounded in the hand, brought ''Thunderer'' alongside ''Achille'' and led a [[naval boarding|boarding action]] which captured ''Achille''. Nearby, ''Thetis'' successfully brought ''Bouffone'' to action, holding up the French frigate long enough that ''Modeste'' was able to come within range. With his frigate heavily outgunned, the French captain surrendered.<ref name=\"LG1\"/>\n\nProby brought the squadron and its prizes back to [[Gibraltar]], where the wounded were treated in the city's hospitals. British casualties were listed as 17 killed and 114 wounded, all on ''Thunderer'' and most from the gun explosion.<ref name=\"LG1\"/> ''Thunderer'' had also taken severe damage to the masts and rigging from French shot. The only other heavily engaged British ship was ''Thetis'' which had also suffered damage to masts and rigging, but received no casualties. According to Proby's dispatch to the [[Admiralty]], no record of French losses was made in the aftermath of the battle.<ref name=\"LG1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=50em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book\n | last = Clowes\n | first = William Laird\n | authorlink = William Laird Clowes\n | year = 1997\n | origyear= 1900\n | chapter = \n | title = The Royal Navy, A History from the Earliest Times to 1900, Volume III\n | publisher = Chatham Publishing\n | location = London\n | isbn = 1-86176-012-4\n}}\n\n{{coord missing|Atlantic Ocean}}\n\n[[Category:Naval battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1761]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of the Seven Years' War]]\n", "name_user": "Snagemit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_of_17_July_1761"}
{"title_page": "Ancient Greek military personal equipment", "text_new": "[[File:Athenian hoplite.jpg|right|thumb|A Greek hoplite with [[muscle cuirass]], spear, shield, [[Corinthian helmet]] and sheathed sword.]]\n'''Ancient Greek weapons and armor''' were primarily geared towards combat between individuals. Their primary technique  was called the [[phalanx]], a formation consisting of massed shield wall, which required heavy frontal armor and medium-ranged weapons such as spears.<ref name=\"Holmes2008\">{{cite book|author=Richard Holmes|title=Weapon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2mUFrAt0x54C&pg=PA40|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=1 April 2008|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|isbn=978-1-4053-1619-4|pages=40}}</ref> Soldiers were required to provide their own [[panoply]], which could prove expensive,<ref name=\"Batchelor2008\">{{cite book|author=Stephen Batchelor|title=The Ancient Greeks For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpwzGEFPb8sC&pg=PA59|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=23 September 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-98787-2|pages=59}}</ref> however the lack of any official peace-keeping force meant that most Greek citizens carried weapons as a matter of course for self-defence.<ref name=\"Sallares1991\">{{cite book|author=Robert Sallares|title=The Ecology of the Ancient Greek World|url=https://archive.org/details/ecologyofancien00sall|url-access=registration|accessdate=29 May 2012|year=1991|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-2615-5|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ecologyofancien00sall/page/406 406]}}</ref> Because individuals provided their own equipment, there was considerable diversity in arms and armour among the Hellenistic troops.<ref name=\"Pritchett1986\">{{cite book|author=William Kendrick Pritchett|title=Studies in Ancient Greek Topography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qjrnYZRHgX4C&pg=PA23|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=8 January 1986|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-09698-1|pages=24}}</ref>\n\nThe poorest citizens, unable to afford the purchase or upkeep of military equipment, operated on the battlefield as ''[[psiloi]]'' or [[peltasts]]; fast, mobile skirmishing troops.\n\nWeapons were primarily constructed from iron, wood and bronze.\n\n==Personal weapons==\n\n===Spears===\n[[File:Ancient Macedonian soldiers, from the tomb of Agios Athanasios, Greece.jpg|thumb|Paintings of [[Ancient Macedonia]]n [[Ancient Macedonian army|soldiers]], arms, and armaments, from the tomb of [[Agios Athanasios, Thessaloniki]] in Greece, 4th century BC]]\nThe primary weapon that was used by Greek troops was a two-to-three meter spear with a leaf-shaped blade at one end and a short spike at the other known as the ''[[Dory (spear)|doru]]''. The spear head was usually made of bronze or iron but which one was more prominently used is still an open question.  The doru was used one-handed (the other hand supporting the soldier's shield).<ref name=\"Gabriel2002\">{{cite book|author=Richard A. Gabriel|title=The Great Armies of Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y1ngxn_xTOIC&pg=PA177|accessdate=30 May 2012|year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-97809-9|pages=177}}</ref> Mounted cavalry were known to have used a thinner spear or very long lance (''[[xyston]]'') which provided a range advantage over shorter infantry spears.<ref name=\"Spence2002\">{{cite book|author=Iain Spence|title=Historical Dictionary of Ancient Greek Warfare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IidfC0UMHdYC&pg=PA89|accessdate=30 May 2012|year=2002|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-4099-7|pages=89}}</ref>\n\nUnder [[Philip II of Macedon]], hoplites were equipped with extremely long spears (up to 21 feet) called ''[[sarissa|sarrisae]]''. Used in conjunction with the phalanx formation, this made an impregnable wall of spears in front of the infantry; the enemy's shorter weaponry could not reach the phalanx because of the ''sarissae''\n.<ref name=\"Grote1856\">{{cite book|author=George Grote|title=A history of Greece|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i0wbAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA77|accessdate=7 June 2012|year=1856|publisher=John Murray|pages=77\u201379}}</ref>\n\n===Sword===\nAs a secondary weapon, hoplites are known to have carried a short sword known as the ''[[xiphos]]'' which was made from iron or bronze depending on the era. This was used in the event of a broken spear, or if close melee combat was necessary.<ref name=\"KINDERSLEYStaff2010\">{{cite book|author1=DORLING KINDERSLEY|author2=Dorling Kindersley Publishing Staff|title=Swords|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vfhw5Au5RJEC&pg=PA30|accessdate=30 May 2012|date=1 April 2010|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Limited|isbn=978-1-4053-5136-2|pages=30}}</ref> Hoplites mounted on horseback likely used a heavier, curved sword known as the ''[[kopis]]'', meaning \"chopper\" in the Greek language.\n<ref name=\"Batchelor2008\"/><ref name=\"SekundaSekunda1986\"/> Light infantry known as peltasts would carry a number of javelins used to pepper enemy formations, avoiding close combat whenever possible. The job of the peltast was not to engage in formation combat, therefore, many carried nothing more than javelins.\n\n===Ranged weapons===\nHand-to-hand, light support troops such as the ''psiloi'' were often armed with ranged weapons. Popular ranged weapons were the bow (''[[Toxotai|toxa]]''), javelin (''[[javelin|akontia]]'') and sling (''[[Sling (weapon)|sfendonai]]''). While the bow was a relatively uncommon weapon (the wooden stave bow used had a limited range), some troops treated their arrows by thrusting them into rotting corpses, thus creating a crude form of biological weapon.<ref name=\"Broyles2004\">{{cite book|author=Janell Broyles|title=Chemical And Biological Weapons In A Post-9/11 World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7t_AWHY5fLkC&pg=PA9|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=1 November 2004|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-0288-7|pages=9}}</ref> Peltast troops commonly used javelins, and hoplites and cavalry troops were also often equipped with javelins for throwing. The javelins used were light spears around 1.5 meters in length, with a bronze head to facilitate recovery of the weapon; they were usually thrown with the aid of an ''[[amentum]]''.{{cn|date=September 2019}} Slings used both lead pellets and stones; stones were also commonly thrown by hand.<ref name=\"Pritchett1991\">{{cite book|author=William Kendrick Pritchett|title=The Greek State at War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z1kbyWNJIt0C&pg=PA1|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=5 June 1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-07374-6|pages=1\u201315}}</ref>\n\n==Armor==\n[[File:Ancient Mieza, Macedonian tombs of Lefkadia, Tomb of Lyson and Kallikles a72b9b998c2e98a1390dbae9e032ea1c.jpg|thumb|[[Ancient Macedonia]]n paintings of [[Hellenistic]]-era military armor, arms, and gear from the [[Tomb of Lyson and Kallikles]] in ancient [[Mieza, Macedonia|Mieza]] (modern-day Lefkadia), [[Imathia]], [[Central Macedonia]], Greece, dated 2nd century BC.]]\n''[[Linothorax]]'' armor made out of linen fabric was the most common form of infantry torso armor, being cheap and relatively light. Bronze breastplate armor was also used, in forms such as a [[Cuirass|bell cuirass]]. Little other armor was worn, and fatal blows to unprotected areas (such as the bladder or neck) are recorded in ancient art and poetry.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997\"/> Cavalry armor was designed to be lightweight; over a sleeveless tunic called a ''chitoniskos'' the cavalry soldier would wear a [[muscle cuirass]] designed to leave the arms as free as possible.<ref name=\"SekundaSekunda1986\">{{cite book|author1=Nick Sekunda|author2=Nicholas Sekunda|title=The Ancient Greeks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=93-ZFvr-lkoC&pg=PA18|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=22 May 1986|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-0-85045-686-8|pages=18}}</ref> Hoplites wore [[greave]]s to protect the lower leg, as did cavalry, but otherwise the torso and head were the only body parts protected by armor.\n\n==Shields==\nThe most vital part of the panoply was the [[Aspis]], a large, round shield commonly made from a layer of bronze, wood, and leather. The ''hoplon'' was around a meter in diameter, and weighed around 7.3 kg (16&nbsp;lbs), making it uncomfortable to hold for long periods.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997\">{{cite book|author1=David Sacks|author2=Oswyn Murray|title=A Dictionary of the Ancient Greek World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KeEjUjSaDA0C&pg=PA118|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=6 February 1997|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-511206-1|pages=117}}</ref> Peltasts were armed with wicker shields called ''pelte'', which were much lighter, allowing for greater movement on the battlefield. These were designed to defend against in-coming javelins from opposing peltasts, not necessarily to fend off the thrust of a spear or sword.<ref name=\"Lendon2006\">{{cite book|author=J. E. Lendon|title=Soldiers and Ghosts: A History of Battle in Classical Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gr0H_wr9J4wC&pg=PA96|accessdate=30 May 2012|date=22 August 2006|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-11979-4|pages=96}}</ref>\n\n==Helmets==\n\nHelmets for the infantry came in various types . The earliest standard hoplite helmet was the [[Corinthian helmet]], developed around 600BC.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997\"/> Later, this was replaced by the [[Phrygian type helmet|Phrygian helmet]] and [[Chalcidian helmet]], which were lighter and did not impair the wearer's vision or hearing so severely. Helmets often had a horsehair crest, for decorative purposes and as an additional level of protection. The [[Boeotian helmet]] was commonly used by cavalry troops due to their need for unimpeded vision and hearing. Helmets were mainly used for protecting the head but leaving the eyes, mouth and nose unprotected.<ref name=\"Heckel2002\">{{cite book|author=Waldemar Heckel|title=The Wars of Alexander the Great: 336-323 BC|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p3D_QHiHdpAC&pg=PA25|accessdate=30 May 2012|date=25 July 2002|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84176-473-3|pages=25}}</ref>\n\n==Other==\n\n===Chariots===\nThe [[Chariot#Greece|chariot]], though ineffective for warfare in the hilly terrain of the Greek mainland, was used by the [[Mycenean Greek|Myceneans]] in some circumstances. The vehicle used was generally a single-axled chariot, drawn by two horses and carrying two passengers (a driver and a spearman or archer); the construction was generally bronze-plated wood.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997_58\">{{cite book|author1=David Sacks|author2=Oswyn Murray|title=A Dictionary of the Ancient Greek World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KeEjUjSaDA0C&pg=PA58|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=6 February 1997|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-511206-1|pages=58\u201359}}</ref>\n\n===Catapults===\nThe Ancient Greeks used two principal types of heavy catapults as [[siege engines]]. The ''ethytonos'' was a type of stationary bow, mounted on a tripod and similar in design to a [[ballista]].<ref name=\"Denny2007\">{{cite book|author=Mark Denny|title=Ingenium: Five Machines That Changed the World|url=https://archive.org/details/ingeniumfivemach0000denn|url-access=registration|accessdate=20 June 2012|date=4 May 2007|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-8586-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ingeniumfivemach0000denn/page/26 26]\u201327}}</ref> A larger version, the ''palintonos'', fired stone projectiles.<ref name=\"CorfisWolfe2000\">{{cite book|author1=Ivy A. Corfis|author2=Michael Wolfe|title=The Medieval City Under Siege|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OJIFpd09vCgC&pg=PA135|accessdate=20 June 2012|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-756-6|pages=135}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military history of ancient Greece]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Athenian hoplite.jpg|right|thumb|A Greek hoplite with [[muscle cuirass]], spear, shield, [[Corinthian helmet]] and sheathed sword.]]\n'''Ancient Greek weapons and armor''' were primarily geared towards combat between individuals. Their primary technique  was called the [[phalanx]], a formation consisting of massed shield wall, which required heavy frontal armor and medium-ranged weapons such as spears.<ref name=\"Holmes2008\">{{cite book|author=Richard Holmes|title=Weapon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2mUFrAt0x54C&pg=PA40|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=1 April 2008|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|isbn=978-1-4053-1619-4|pages=40}}</ref> Soldiers were required to provide their own [[panoply]], which could prove expensive,<ref name=\"Batchelor2008\">{{cite book|author=Stephen Batchelor|title=The Ancient Greeks For Dummies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HpwzGEFPb8sC&pg=PA59|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=23 September 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-98787-2|pages=59}}</ref> however the lack of any official peace-keeping force meant that most Greek citizens carried weapons as a matter of course for self-defence.<ref name=\"Sallares1991\">{{cite book|author=Robert Sallares|title=The Ecology of the Ancient Greek World|url=https://archive.org/details/ecologyofancien00sall|url-access=registration|accessdate=29 May 2012|year=1991|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-2615-5|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ecologyofancien00sall/page/406 406]}}</ref> Because individuals provided their own equipment, there was considerable diversity in arms and armour among the Hellenistic troops.<ref name=\"Pritchett1986\">{{cite book|author=William Kendrick Pritchett|title=Studies in Ancient Greek Topography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qjrnYZRHgX4C&pg=PA23|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=8 January 1986|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-09698-1|pages=24}}</ref>\n\nThe poorest citizens, unable to afford the purchase or upkeep of military equipment, operated on the battlefield as ''[[psiloi]]'' or [[peltasts]]; fast, mobile skirmishing troops.\n\nWeapons were primarily constructed from iron, wood and bronze.\n\n==Personal weapons==\n\n===Spears===\n[[File:Ancient Macedonian soldiers, from the tomb of Agios Athanasios, Greece.jpg|thumb|Paintings of [[Ancient Macedonia]]n [[Ancient Macedonian army|soldiers]], arms, and armaments, from the tomb of [[Agios Athanasios, Thessaloniki]] in Greece, 4th century BC]]\nThe primary weapon that was used by Greek troops was a two-to-three meter spear with a leaf-shaped blade at one end and a short spike at the other known as the ''[[Dory (spear)|doru]]''. The spear head was usually made of bronze or iron but which one was more prominently used is still an open question.  The doru was used one-handed (the other hand supporting the soldier's shield).<ref name=\"Gabriel2002\">{{cite book|author=Richard A. Gabriel|title=The Great Armies of Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y1ngxn_xTOIC&pg=PA177|accessdate=30 May 2012|year=2002|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-97809-9|pages=177}}</ref> Mounted cavalry were known to have used a thinner spear or very long lance (''[[xyston]]'') which provided a range advantage over shorter infantry spears.<ref name=\"Spence2002\">{{cite book|author=Iain Spence|title=Historical Dictionary of Ancient Greek Warfare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IidfC0UMHdYC&pg=PA89|accessdate=30 May 2012|year=2002|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-4099-7|pages=89}}</ref>\n\nUnder [[Philip II of Macedon]], hoplites were equipped with extremely long spears (up to 21 feet) called ''[[sarissa|sarrisae]]''. Used in conjunction with the phalanx formation, this made an impregnable wall of spears in front of the infantry; the enemy's shorter weaponry could not reach the phalanx because of the ''sarissae''\n.<ref name=\"Grote1856\">{{cite book|author=George Grote|title=A history of Greece|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i0wbAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA77|accessdate=7 June 2012|year=1856|publisher=John Murray|pages=77\u201379}}</ref>\n\n===Sword===\nAs a secondary weapon, hoplites are known to have carried a short sword known as the ''[[xiphos]]'' which was made from iron or bronze depending on the era. This was used in the event of a broken spear, or if close melee combat was necessary.<ref name=\"KINDERSLEYStaff2010\">{{cite book|author1=DORLING KINDERSLEY|author2=Dorling Kindersley Publishing Staff|title=Swords|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vfhw5Au5RJEC&pg=PA30|accessdate=30 May 2012|date=1 April 2010|publisher=Dorling Kindersley Limited|isbn=978-1-4053-5136-2|pages=30}}</ref> Hoplites mounted on horseback likely used a heavier, curved sword known as the ''[[kopis]]'', meaning \"chopper\" in the Greek language.\n<ref name=\"Batchelor2008\"/><ref name=\"SekundaSekunda1986\"/> Light infantry known as peltasts would carry a number of javelins used to pepper enemy formations, avoiding close combat whenever possible. The job of the peltast was not to engage in formation combat, therefore, many carried nothing more than javelins.\n\n===Ranged weapons===\nHand-to-hand, light support troops such as the ''psiloi'' were often armed with ranged weapons. Popular ranged weapons were the bow (''[[Toxotai|toxa]]''), javelin (''[[javelin|akontia]]'') and sling (''[[Sling (weapon)|sfendonai]]''). While the bow was a relatively uncommon weapon (the wooden stave bow used had a limited range), some troops treated their arrows by thrusting them into rotting corpses, thus creating a crude form of biological weapon.<ref name=\"Broyles2004\">{{cite book|author=Janell Broyles|title=Chemical And Biological Weapons In A Post-9/11 World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7t_AWHY5fLkC&pg=PA9|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=1 November 2004|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-4042-0288-7|pages=9}}</ref> Peltast troops commonly used javelins, and hoplites and cavalry troops were also often equipped with javelins for throwing. The javelins used were light spears around 1.5 meters in length, with a bronze head to facilitate recovery of the weapon; they were usually thrown with the aid of an ''[[amentum]]''.{{cn|date=September 2019}} Slings used both lead pellets and stones; stones were also commonly thrown by hand.<ref name=\"Pritchett1991\">{{cite book|author=William Kendrick Pritchett|title=The Greek State at War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z1kbyWNJIt0C&pg=PA1|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=5 June 1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-07374-6|pages=1\u201315}}</ref>\n\n==Armor==\n[[File:Ancient Mieza, Macedonian tombs of Lefkadia, Tomb of Lyson and Kallikles a72b9b998c2e98a1390dbae9e032ea1c.jpg|thumb|[[Ancient Macedonia]]n paintings of [[Hellenistic]]-era military armor, arms, and gear from the [[Tomb of Lyson and Kallikles]] in ancient [[Mieza, Macedonia|Mieza]] (modern-day Lefkadia), [[Imathia]], [[Central Macedonia]], Greece, dated 2nd century BC.]]\n''[[Linothorax]]'' armor made out of linen fabric was the most common form of infantry torso armor, being cheap and relatively light. Bronze breastplate armor was also used, in forms such as a [[Cuirass|bell cuirass]]. Little other armor was worn, and fatal blows to unprotected areas (such as the bladder or neck) are recorded in ancient art and poetry.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997\"/> Cavalry armor was designed to be lightweight; over a sleeveless tunic called a ''chitoniskos'' the cavalry soldier would wear a [[muscle cuirass]] designed to leave the arms as free as possible.<ref name=\"SekundaSekunda1986\">{{cite book|author1=Nick Sekunda|author2=Nicholas Sekunda|title=The Ancient Greeks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=93-ZFvr-lkoC&pg=PA18|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=22 May 1986|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-0-85045-686-8|pages=18}}</ref> Hoplites wore [[greave]]s to protect the lower leg, as did cavalry, but otherwise the torso and head were the only body parts protected by armor.\n\n==Shields==\nThe most vital part of the panoply was the [[Aspis]], a large, round shield commonly made from a layer of bronze, wood, and leather. The ''hoplon'' was around a meter in diameter, and weighed around 7.3 kg (16&nbsp;lbs), making it uncomfortable to hold for long periods.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997\">{{cite book|author1=David Sacks|author2=Oswyn Murray|title=A Dictionary of the Ancient Greek World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KeEjUjSaDA0C&pg=PA118|accessdate=29 May 2012|date=6 February 1997|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-511206-1|pages=117}}</ref> Peltasts were armed with wicker shields called ''pelte'', which were much lighter, allowing for greater movement on the battlefield. These were designed to defend against in-coming javelins from opposing peltasts, not necessarily to fend off the thrust of a spear or sword.<ref name=\"Lendon2006\">{{cite book|author=J. E. Lendon|title=Soldiers and Ghosts: A History of Battle in Classical Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gr0H_wr9J4wC&pg=PA96|accessdate=30 May 2012|date=22 August 2006|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-11979-4|pages=96}}</ref>The shield was used in every battle, the soldiers didn't go on battle without it. It weighed approx. 16 Ibs\n\n==Helmets==\n\nHelmets for the infantry came in various types . The earliest standard hoplite helmet was the [[Corinthian helmet]], developed around 600BC.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997\"/> Later, this was replaced by the [[Phrygian type helmet|Phrygian helmet]] and [[Chalcidian helmet]], which were lighter and did not impair the wearer's vision or hearing so severely. Helmets often had a horsehair crest, for decorative purposes and as an additional level of protection. The [[Boeotian helmet]] was commonly used by cavalry troops due to their need for unimpeded vision and hearing. Helmets were mainly used for protecting the head but leaving the eyes, mouth and nose unprotected.<ref name=\"Heckel2002\">{{cite book|author=Waldemar Heckel|title=The Wars of Alexander the Great: 336-323 BC|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p3D_QHiHdpAC&pg=PA25|accessdate=30 May 2012|date=25 July 2002|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84176-473-3|pages=25}}</ref>\n\n==Other==\n\n===Chariots===\nThe [[Chariot#Greece|chariot]], though ineffective for warfare in the hilly terrain of the Greek mainland, was used by the [[Mycenean Greek|Myceneans]] in some circumstances. The vehicle used was generally a single-axled chariot, drawn by two horses and carrying two passengers (a driver and a spearman or archer); the construction was generally bronze-plated wood.<ref name=\"SacksMurray1997_58\">{{cite book|author1=David Sacks|author2=Oswyn Murray|title=A Dictionary of the Ancient Greek World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KeEjUjSaDA0C&pg=PA58|accessdate=7 June 2012|date=6 February 1997|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-511206-1|pages=58\u201359}}</ref>\n\n===Catapults===\nThe Ancient Greeks used two principal types of heavy catapults as [[siege engines]]. The ''ethytonos'' was a type of stationary bow, mounted on a tripod and similar in design to a [[ballista]].<ref name=\"Denny2007\">{{cite book|author=Mark Denny|title=Ingenium: Five Machines That Changed the World|url=https://archive.org/details/ingeniumfivemach0000denn|url-access=registration|accessdate=20 June 2012|date=4 May 2007|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-8586-0|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ingeniumfivemach0000denn/page/26 26]\u201327}}</ref> A larger version, the ''palintonos'', fired stone projectiles.<ref name=\"CorfisWolfe2000\">{{cite book|author1=Ivy A. Corfis|author2=Michael Wolfe|title=The Medieval City Under Siege|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OJIFpd09vCgC&pg=PA135|accessdate=20 June 2012|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-0-85115-756-6|pages=135}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Military history of ancient Greece]]\n", "name_user": "Ornicus", "label": "safe"