{"title_page": "Colonial Chile", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{History of Chile}}\nIn Chilean [[historiography]], '''Colonial Chile''' ({{lang-es|link=no|la colonia}}) is the period from 1600 to 1810, beginning with the [[Destruction of the Seven Cities]] and ending with the onset of the [[Chilean War of Independence]]. During this time the Chilean heartland was ruled by [[Captaincy General of Chile]]. The period was characterized by a lengthy conflict between Spaniards and native [[Mapuche]]s known as the [[Arauco War]]. Colonial society was divided in distinct groups including [[Peninsulars]], [[Criollo people|Criollos]], [[Mestizo]]s, [[Indigenous peoples in South America|Indians]] and [[African Chilean|Black people]].\n\nRelative to other Spanish colonies Chile was a \"poor and dangerous\" place.<ref name=Hojman/>{{efn-ua|While not falling in the ''sensu stricto'' colonial period the inhabitants of Santiago in the mid-16th century were notoriously poorly dressed as result of a lack of supplies with some Spanish even resorting to dress with [[hide (skin)|hides]] from dogs, cats, [[South American sea lion|sea lions]] and [[South American fox|foxes]].<ref name=leon1991>{{cite book |last=Le\u00f3n |first=Leonardo|author-link=Leonardo Le\u00f3n |title=La merma de la sociadad ind\u00edgena en Chile central y la \u00faltima guerra de los promaucaes |url=http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/archivos2/pdfs/MC0012923.pdf |year=1991 |edition= |publisher=Institute of Amerindian Studies, University of St. Andrews |isbn=1873617003 |language=Spanish|pages=13\u201316}}<!--|accessdate=August 27, 2019 --></ref>}}\n\n==Society==\n\n===Societal groups===\n[[File:Baile del Santiago antiguo.jpg|thumb|300px|\"''Baile del Santiago antiguo''\" by [[Pedro Subercaseaux]]. Chile's colonial high society were made up by landowners and government officials.]]\nThe Chilean colonial society was based on a [[caste system]]. Local of [[Criollo people|criollo]]s (American born Spaniards) enjoyed privileges like the [[ownership]] of [[encomienda]]s (Indian labour jurisdictions) and were allowed to access some public charges like [[Corregidor (position)|corregidor]] or [[alf\u00e9rez]]. [[Mestizo]]s made up initially a small group but came with time to make up the bulk of Chilean society becoming more numerous than indigenous peoples.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Mestizos were not a homogeneous group and were judged more by appearance than by actual ancestry.<ref name=villalobos186>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 186.</ref> Indians enjoyed the lowest prestige among societal groups in colonial Chile, many of them were used as cheap labour in encomienda but their numbers decreased over time due to [[diseases]] and [[mestization]]. [[Pehuenche]]'s, [[Huilliche]]s and Mapuches living south of [[La Frontera, Chile|La Frontera]] were not part of the colonial society since they were outside the ''de facto'' borders of Chile.\n\nSpanish agriculture, centered on the hacienda, absorbed most of the scattered and declining indigenous populations of Central Chile.<ref name=migracioneslocales>{{Cite journal|title=Migraciones locales y asentamiento ind\u00edgena en las estancias espa\u00f1olas de Chile central, 1580-1650|journal=[[Historia (history of the Americas journal)|Historia]]|volume=49|issue=1|doi=10.4067/S0717-71942016000100004|url=https://scielo.conicyt.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0717-71942016000100004&script=sci_arttext#nb29|year=2016|language=Spanish|doi-access=free}}</ref> Thus populations that had previously lived apart in their own villages (''pueblo de indios'') from their Spanish masters begun to live in Spanish estancias.<ref name=migracioneslocales/> In Central Chile the dwindling population of [[Picunche]]s occurred in parallel to import of [[Slavery of Mapuches|Mapuche and Huilliche slaves]] from Araucan\u00eda and Chilo\u00e9,{{efn-ua|It is possible that slaves exported from Chilo\u00e9 included some few [[Chono]] and [[Poya people|Poyas]].<ref>{{Cite book|chapter=El pueblo chono: de vagabundo y pagano a cristiano y sedentario mestizado|journal=|url=http://www.turismocientifico.cl/admin/apps/filemanager/repository/%C3%A1reas%20del%20conocimiento/Poblamiento,%20historia%20y%20cultura/Antropologia/Etnias/Al%20Pueblo%20Chono.pdf|last=Urbina Burgos|first=Rodolfo|pages=325\u2013346|title=Orbis incognitvs: avisos y legados del Nuevo Mundo|year=2007|publisher=Universidad de Huelva|location=Huelva|ISBN=9788496826243|language=Spanish}}</ref>}} as well as the arrival of indigenous people from [[Peru]], [[Tucum\u00e1n]] and the transfer of encomienda [[Huarpe]]s from [[Cuyo (Argentina)|Cuyo]].<ref name=migracioneslocales/><ref name=villalobosHacienda2/> This mix of disparate populations cohabitating with the Spanish contributed to the loss of indigenous identities.<ref name=migracioneslocales/> \n\nFor many years, Spanish-descent settlers and religious orders imported African slaves to the country, which in the early 19th century constituted 1.5% of the national population.<ref>{{Citation\n| last      = Mellafe\n| first     = Rolando\n| title     = La introducci\u00f3n de la esclavitud negra en Chile: Tr\u00e1fico y rutas\n| publisher = Universidad de Chile\n| place     = Santiago de Chile\n| year      = 1959\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> Despite this, the [[Afro-Chilean]] population was negligible, reaching a height of only 2,500 \u2013 or 0.1% of the total population \u2013 during the colonial period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mazinger.sisib.uchile.cl/repositorio/lb/ciencias_quimicas_y_farmaceuticas/medinae/ |title=Elementos de Salud P\u00fablica, section 5.2.6 |publisher=University of Chile |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916211140/http://mazinger.sisib.uchile.cl/repositorio/lb/ciencias_quimicas_y_farmaceuticas/medinae/ |archivedate=September 16, 2009 }}</ref> While a minority black slaves had a special status due to their high cost of import<ref name=Villalobos254>Villalobos ''et al.'' 1974, p. 254.</ref> and maintenance.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Black slaves were often used as [[housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeepers]] and other posts of confidence.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Peninsulares, Spaniards born in Spain, were a rather small group in late colonial times, some of them came as government officials and some other as merchants. Their role in high government positions in Chile led to resentment among local criollos.<ref name=villalobos274>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 274.</ref> Mixing of different groups was not uncommon although marriage between members of the different groups was rare.\n\nDuring late colonial times new migration pulses took off leading to large numbers of [[Basque people]] settling in Chile mingling with landowning criollos, forming a new upper class.<ref name=villalobos257-259>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 257\u2013259.</ref> Scholar Luis Thayer Ojeda estimates that during the 17th and 18th centuries fully 45% of all immigrants in [[History of Chile|Chile]] were Basques.<ref>William A. Douglass, Jon Bilbao (2005). \"''[https://books.google.com/books?id=8KzfK1QwxDIC&pg=PA81 Amerikanuak: Basques in the New World]''\". [[University of Nevada Press]]. p. 81. {{ISBN|0-87417-625-5}}</ref> Compared to other Spanish colonies in the Americas the proportion of women among and merchants among Spanish immigrants to Chile were lower and the proportion of non-Spanish immigrants (e.g. French, Irish) higher.<ref name=Hojman>{{Citation\n| last  = Hojman\n| first = David E.\n| title = The Dutch invasion of colonial Chiloe and early Chilean exceptionalism: A critical juncture and counterfactuals approach\n| pages   = 1\u201348\n| url     = https://www.liv.ac.uk/media/livacuk/schoolofmanagement/docs/drive/The,Dutch,invasion,of,colonial,Chiloe,and,early,Chilean,exceptionalism.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, the Diocese of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Concepci\u00f3n|Concepci\u00f3n]] conducted a census to the south of the [[Maule river]]; however, this did not include the indigenous population \u2013 at that time estimated at 8,000 people \u2013 nor the inhabitants of the province of Chilo\u00e9. It put the total population at 210,567, of which 86.1% was native Spaniards and 10% were Indian, with a remaining 3.7% of Africans, [[mulatto]]s, and mestizo descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ine.cl/canales/usuarios/cedoc_online/censos/pdf/censo_1813.pdf |title=INE \u2013 Censo de 1813. Introducci\u00f3n |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2011-09-22}}</ref> Other estimates in the late 17th century indicate that the population reached a maximum total of 152,000, consisting of 72% whites and mestizos, 18% Indians, and 10% blacks and mulattos.<ref>[http://www.glamorama.cl/medio/articulo/0,0,38035857_152309033_151837148,00.html Icarito \u2013 La Colonia:Poblaci\u00f3n y sociedad]{{dead link|date=December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Sex and marriage===\nIndigenous women in the colonial society were noted, from a Spanish point of view, for their sexual liberalism and engaged often sexually with men from other ethnicities.<ref name=privada>{{Citation\n| last  = Retamal \u00c1.\n| first = Julio\n| chapter = Fidelidad conyugal en el Chile colonial\n| editor-last  = Sagredo\n| editor-first = Rafael\n| editor-last2  = Gazmuri\n| editor-first2 = Cristi\u00e1n\n| title = Historia de la vida privada en Chile\n| volume = 1\n| pages  = 53\u201363\n| publisher = Aguilar Chilena de Ediciones\n| place = Santiago de Chile\n| publication-date = 2005\n| edition = 4th\n| isbn = 956-239-337-2\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> The same was true for the black slaves who due to their \"many\" intercourses with other groups were strictly prohibited by law to engage in sexual activities with other ethnicities in order to avoid the proliferation of black individuals.<ref name=privada/>\n\n16th century Spaniards are known to have been pessimistic about marriage.<ref name=privada/> Many of the initial [[conquistador]]es had left their wives in Spain and engaged in [[adultery]] in Chile.<ref name=privada/> Examples of this is [[Pedro de Valdivia]] who held [[In\u00e9s de Su\u00e1rez]] as lover.<ref name=privada/> Adultery was explicitly forbidden for Catholics and the [[Council of Trent]] (1545\u20131563) made the climate prone for accusations of adultery.<ref name=privada/> Over the course of the 16th, 17th and 18th centuries marital fidelity increased in Chile.<ref name=privada/>\n\n==Political organization==\n{{see also|Captaincy General of Chile|Governorate of Chilo\u00e9|Intendancy of Chilo\u00e9}}\nThe government of Chile or ''Nueva Toledo'' was created by Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] in 1534 and placed under the governorship of [[Diego de Almagro]]. It ran south from 14\u00b0 S to 25\u00b0 S latitude, as far south as present-day [[Taltal]].  ''[[Capitan\u00eda General de Chile]]'', or ''Gobernaci\u00f3n de Chile'', remained a colony of the Spanish Empire until 1818 when it declared itself independent.  In the mid Eighteenth Century, the [[Bourbon Reforms#Spanish America|Bourbon administrative reforms]] divided Chile into [[intendencias]] (provinces) and further into ''partidos'' (counties) which were also known by the older term of ''corregimientos''. The ''partidos'' were further divided into ''distritos'' (districts) akin to Chile's modern [[Communes of Chile|communes]].<ref name=\"Cobos\">{{Cite book|author=Cobos, Mar\u00eda Teresa |year=1989 |title=La divisi\u00f3n pol\u00edtico-administrativa de Chile, 1541\u20131811 |language=es|location=Valpara\u00edso, Chile |publisher=Instituto de Historia, Vicerrector\u00eda Acad\u00e9mica, Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de Valpara\u00edso |oclc=30686100}}</ref> In 1786 two intendencias were created: Santiago and [[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]. By the end of the 18th century, Santiago was divided into thirteen ''partidos''.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Carvallo y Goyeneche, Vicente |authorlink=Vicente Carvallo y Goyeneche |year=1875 |title=Descripci\u00f3n Hist\u00f3rico Geograf\u00eda del Reino de Chile (part 3)|language=es|journal=Colecci\u00f3n de Historiadores de Chile y documentos relativos a la Historia Nacional |volume=10 |publisher=Sociedad Chilena de Historia y Geograf\u00eda |location=Santiago de Chile |url=http://www.memoriachilena.cl/archivos2/pdfs/MC0008930.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007230529/http://www.memoriachilena.cl/archivos2/pdfs/MC0008930.pdf |archivedate=October 7, 2007 |url-status=live}} manuscript 1795.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" align=\"center\" width=60%\n|- bgcolor=\"#ececec\"\n! ''Partido''!! [[Administrative centre]]\n|-\n|Santiago\n|[[Santiago|Ciudad de Santiago del Nuevo Extremo]]\n|-\n|Copiap\u00f3\n|[[Copiap\u00f3|Villa de San Francisco de la Selva]]\n|-\n|Huasco\n|[[Freirina|Villa de Santa Rosa del Huasco]]\n|-\n|Coquimbo\n|[[La Serena, Chile|Ciudad de San Bartolom\u00e9 de la Serena]]\n|-\n|Cuzc\u00faz\n|[[Illapel|Villa de San Rafael de Rozas]]\n|-\n|Quillota\n|[[Quillota|Villa de San Mart\u00edn de la Concha]]\n|-\n|Valpara\u00edso\n|[[Valpara\u00edso|Puerto de Valpara\u00edso]]\n|-\n|Aconcagua\n|[[San Felipe, Chile|Villa de San Felipe el Real]]\n|-\n|Melipilla\n|[[Melipilla|Villa de San Jos\u00e9 de Logro\u00f1o]]\n|-\n|Rancagua\n|[[Rancagua|Villa de Santa Cruz de Triana]]\n|-\n|Colchagua\n|[[San Fernando, Chile|Villa de San Fernando el Real de Tinguiririca]]\n|-\n|Curic\u00f3\n|[[Curic\u00f3|Villa de San Jos\u00e9 de la Buenavista]]\n|-\n|Maule\n|[[Talca|Villa de San Agust\u00edn de Talca]]\n|-\n|}\n\nThe intendencia of Concepcion had six ''partidos'': Cauquenes, Chill\u00e1n, Itata, Rere, Laja, and Puchacay. A third intendencia, Coquimbo was created in 1810. The area of [[Chilo\u00e9 Province|Chilo\u00e9]] may be considered a fourth intendencia, but instead of reporting to the governor/capitain it reported directly to the viceroy, beginning in 1777.<ref name=\"Cobos\" /><ref>{{Cite book|author=Encina, Francisco Antonio|year=1952 |title=Historia de Chile: Desde la prehistoria hasta 1891 |location=Santiago |language=es|edition=second | publisher=Nascimento| volume=IV |page= 643}}</ref> The ''intendencia'', ''partido'' and ''distrito'' system was replaced in 1822 with ''departamentos'', ''distritos'' and ''cabildos''.\n\n==Labor forms==\n\n===Encomienda===\nBeyond subsistence the 16th century economy of Chile was oriented towards large-scale production. Spanish colonizers used large amounts of indigenous labour following the slave labour system used in the [[sugar cane]] plantations of the [[Mediterranean islands]] and [[Macaronesia]]. This system of labour successively killed the production base leading to the imposition of the [[encomienda|encomienda system]] by the Spanish Crown in order to prevent excesses. In Chile Spanish settlers managed to continue to exploit indigenous labour under slave like conditions despite the implementation of the encomienda. Rich Spanish settlers had over time to face opposition to their mode of production by [[Jesuit]]s, Spanish officials and indigenous [[Mapuche]]s.<ref name=GZ23-25>Salazar 1985, pp. 23\u201325.</ref>\n\nOver the course of the 17th century the indigenous population of Chile declined making the [[encomienda]]s less and less important.<ref name=villalobosHacienda>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 160\u2013165.</ref> Chilean encomenderos who had encomiendas in [[Cuyo (Argentina)|Cuyo]], across the Andes, introduced to Chile indigenous [[Huarpe people|Huarpes]] who they hired to other Spanish without encomiendas.<ref name=villalobosHacienda2>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 166\u2013170.</ref>\n\nThe encomienda system was abolished in 1782 in [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago|Chilo\u00e9]] and in 1789 in the rest of Chile and in 1791 in the whole Spanish Empire.<ref name=Urbina/><ref name=llanquihue>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.diariollanquihue.cl/prontus4_nots/site/artic/20070728/pags/20070728230653.html La rebeli\u00f3n huilliche de 1712] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203011346/http://www.diariollanquihue.cl/prontus4_nots/site/artic/20070728/pags/20070728230653.html |date=December 3, 2013 }} ''[[El Llanquihue]]''. Puplished in July 29, 2007. Retrieved 2012-05-26.</ref><ref name=MCLlaencomienda/><ref name=villalobos>[[Sergio Villalobos|Villalobos, Sergio]]; Silva, Osvaldo; Silva, Fernando and Estelle, Patricio. 1974. ''Historia De Chile''. [[Editorial Universitaria]], Chile. p 237.</ref>\n\n===Inquilinaje===\n{{main|inquilino}}\n\n===Formal slavery===\n{{see also|Afro-Chilean|Slavery of Mapuches|Atlantic slave trade}}\nThe Spanish were familiar with the institution of slavery. In the [[Mediterranean islands]] and [[Macaronesia]] the Spanish and Portuguese had a slave labour system used in [[sugar cane]] plantations.<ref name=GZ23-25/> In the [[Iberian peninsula]] slavery was declining did still occur in the 16th century.<ref name=MCLesclavitud>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-100668.html\n| title = La esclavitud negra en Chile (1536\u20131823)\n| work  = [[Memoria Chilena]]\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = May 30, 2015\n| language = Spanish\n| postscript = .\n}}</ref> The import of black slaves into Chile was a response to a long-term population decline among indigenous peoples.  Slavery was a legal labour form in Chile from 1536 to 1823 but it was never the dominant way of arranging labour. Slavery of black people bloomed from 1580 to 1660. The end of the boom is associated to the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] and Portugal's loss of several slave trading posts in Africa.<ref name=MCLesclavitud/>\n\nFormal slavery of indigenous people was prohibited by the Spanish Crown. The 1598\u20131604 [[Mapuche]] uprising that ended with the [[Destruction of the Seven Cities]] made the Spanish in 1608 declare slavery legal for those Mapuches caught in war.<ref name=Valenzuela231-233/> Rebelling Mapuches were considered Christian [[Apostasy|apostates]] and could therefore be enslaved according to the church teachings of the day.<ref>{{cite book |last=Foerster |first=Rolf |date=1993 |title=Introducci\u00f3n a la religiosidad mapuche |url= |location= |publisher=[[Editorial universitaria]] |page=21 |language=Spanish |isbn= |access-date= }}</ref> This legal change formalized Mapuche slavery that was already occurring at the time, with captured Mapuches being treated as property in the way that they were bought and sold among the Spanish. Legalisation made Spanish [[slave raiding]] increasingly common in the [[Arauco War]].<ref name=Valenzuela231-233>Valenzuela M\u00e1rquez 2009, p. 231\u2013233</ref> Mapuche slaves were exported north to [[La Serena, Chile|La Serena]] and [[Lima]].<ref name=Valenzuela234236/> Slavery for Mapuches \"caught in war\" was abolished in 1683 after decades of legal attempts by the Spanish Crown to suppress it. By that time free mestizo labour had become significantly cheaper than ownership of slaves which made [[Mario G\u00f3ngora]] in 1966 conclude that economic factors were behind the abolition.<ref name=Valenzuela234236>Valenzuela M\u00e1rquez 2009, pp. 234\u2013236</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n{{Location map+|Chile|float=right|width=300|caption=Location Spanish settlements within the modern boundaries of Chile in late colonial times. Color of dots shows the date since the settlements have been in continuous existence. 16th century: red dots. 17th century: blue dots. 18th century: yellow dots. Red circles shows areas of indigenous resistance to Spanish penetration by the late 18th century.|places=\n<!-- North-East-->\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-18.483333 |long=-70.333333 |label=[[Arica]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-27.366389 |long=-70.333056 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-28.466389 |long=-71.219167 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-29.9 |long=-71.25 |label=[[La Serena|La Serena]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-31.633333 |long=-71.166667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.251389 |long=-70.931389 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.45 |long=-71.216667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.75 |long=-70.723889 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.833333 |long=-70.616667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.05 |long=-71.616667 |label=[[Valpara\u00edso]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.316667 |long=-71.416667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.45 |long=-70.666667 |label=[[Santiago]]|position=right|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-34.166667 |long=-70.75 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-34.583333 |long=-70.983333 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-34.983333 |long=-71.233333 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-35.433333 |long=-71.666667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.623889 |long=-72.135833 |label=|position=right|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.733333 |long=-72.983333 |label=[[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.25 |long=-73.316667 |label=|position=left|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.5 |long=-72.666667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~\n |Chile\n |label=[[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|Araucan\u00eda]]\n |relief=yes \n |lat=-38.80582 \n |long=-72.601265\n |position=left\n |width=100\n |label_width=8\n |float=right\n |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=40\n |caption=Locationx\n}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-39.890556 |long=-73.393333 |label=[[Valdivia]]|position=left|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~\n |Chile\n |label=[[Futahuillimapu]]\n |relief=yes \n |lat=-40.90582 \n |long=-73.521265\n |position=left\n |width=100\n |label_width=8\n |float=right\n |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=25\n |caption=Locationx\n}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-40.5725 |long=-73.135278 |label=[[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]]|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.7712 |long=-73.1275 |label=|position=right|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.866667 |long=-73.833333 |label=[[Ancud]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.745833 |long=-73.706389 |label=|position=right|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-42.466667 |long=-73.8 |label=[[Castro, Chile|Castro]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n}}\n{{main|Economic history of Chile}}\nThe [[Destruction of the Seven Cities|collapse of the Spanish cities]] in the south following the [[battle of Curalaba]] (1598) meant for the Spaniards the loss of both the main gold districts and the largest indigenous labour sources.<ref name=salazarpinto>Salazar & Pinto 2002, p. 15.</ref> After those dramatic years the colony of Chile became concentrated in the [[Zona Central, Chile|central valley]] which became increasingly populated, explored and economically exploited. Following a tendency common in the whole [[Spanish America]] [[hacienda]]s were formed as the economy moved away from mining and into agriculture and husbandry.<ref name=villalobosHacienda/>\n\nIn the 1650\u20131800 period the Chilean lower classes grew considerably in size.<ref name=GZ49>Salazar 1985, p. 49.</ref> To deal with the poor and landless population a policy of founding cities<ref group=\"note\">These cities were often in fact more of villages or towns due to their size.</ref> and granting lands in their surroundings was implemented.<ref name=GZ49/> From 1730 to 1820 a large number of farmers settled in the outskirts of old cities or formed new cities.<ref>Salazar 1985, p. 58.</ref> Settling as a farmer in the outskirts of old cities ([[La Serena, Chile|La Serena]], [[Valpara\u00edso]], [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]] and [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]) was overall more popular than joining a new city since it secured a larger consumer market for agricultural products.<ref>Salazar 1985, p. 52.</ref> Chilean [[hacienda]]s ([[latifundium|latifundia]]) engaged little in the supply of Chilean cities but focused on international exports for revenues.<ref>Salazar 1985, p. 88.</ref>\n\nHaciendas of central Chile are believed to had become labour-saturated by 1780 generating an \"excess\" population that could not be incorporated into their economy.<ref name=GZ154>Salazar 1985, p. 153\u2013154.</ref> Some of this population settled in the outskirts of larger cities while other migrated to the mining districts of [[Norte Chico, Chile|Norte Chico]].<ref name=GZ154/>\n\n===Agriculture===\n{{see also|Chilean wheat cycle}}\n{{rquote|right|without Chile, Lima would not exist|Viceroy [[Jos\u00e9 de Armend\u00e1riz, 1st Marquis of Castelfuerte|Jos\u00e9 de Armend\u00e1riz]] in 1736<ref>Quoted in [[Diego Barros Arana]]'s ''Hist\u00f3ria general de Chile'', Vol. 16 (Santiago, 1884\u20131902), p. 74.</ref>}}\nChile began exporting cereals to [[Peru]] in 1687 when Peru was struck by both [[1687 Peru earthquake|an earthquake]] and a [[stem rust]] epidemic.<ref name=villalobos1687>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 155\u2013160.</ref> Chilean soil and climatic conditions were better for cereal production than those of Peru and Chilean wheat was cheaper and of better quality than Peruvian wheat.<ref name=villalobos1687/><ref name=collier>Collier, Simon and Sater William F. 2004. ''A History of Chile: 1808\u20132002'' [[Cambridge University Press]]. p. 10.</ref> According to historians [[Sergio Villalobos|Villalobos]] ''et al''. the 1687 events were only the detonant factor for exports to start.<ref name=villalobos1687/> The [[Chilean Central Valley]], La Serena and Concepci\u00f3n were the districts that came to be involved in cereal export to Peru.<ref name=villalobos1687/> It should be pointed out that compared with the 19th century the area cultivated with wheat was very small and production modest.<ref name=collier/>\n\nInitially Chilean [[Latifundium|latifundia]] could not meet the wheat demand due to a labour shortage, so had to incorporate [[Temporary work|temporal workers]] in addition to the permanent staff. Another response by the latifundia to labour shortages was to act as merchants buying wheat produced by independent farmers or from farmers that hired land. In the period 1700 to 1850 this second option was overall more lucrative.<ref>Salazar 1985, pp. 40\u201341</ref>\n\nThe 1687 Peru earthquake also ended a Peruvian wine-boom as the earthquake destroyed [[wine cellar]]s and mud containers used for wine storage.<ref name=Lacoste>{{Citation\n| last  = Lacoste\n| first = Pablo\n| title = La vid y el vino en Am\u00e9rica del Sur: el desplazamiento de los polos vitivin\u00edcolas (siglos XVI al XX)\n| journal = [[Revista Universum]]\n| volume  = 19\n| issue   = 2\n| year    = 2004\n| pages   = 62\u201393\n| url     = http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-23762004000200005&script=sci_arttext&tlng=es\n| doi=10.4067/s0718-23762004000200005\n| doi-access= free\n}}\n\n[http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-23762004000200005&script=sci_arttext&tlng=es ]</ref> The gradual decline of Peruvian wine even caused Peru to import some wine from Chile as it happened in 1795 when Lima imported 5.000 troves (Spanish: ''botijas'') from [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]] in southern Chile.<ref name=Lacoste/><ref name=pozo2>{{Citation\n| last1  = del Pozo\n| first1 = Jos\u00e9\n| lastauthoramp = yes\n| title     = Historia del vino chileno\n| publisher = [[Editorial Universitaria]]\n| year    = 2004\n| pages   = 35\u201345\n}}</ref> This particular export showed the emergence of Chile relative to Peru as a wine-making region.<ref name=Lacoste/>\n\n===Mining===\nCompared to the 16th and 18th centuries Chilean mining activity in the 17th century was very limited.<ref name=villalobos17thmining>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 168.</ref> Chile saw an unprecedented revival of its mining activity in the 18th century with annual gold production rising from 400 to 1000&nbsp;kg over the course of the century and the silver annual production rising from 1000 to 5000&nbsp;kg in the same interval.<ref name=villalobosMining>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 226\u2013227.</ref>\n\n[[File:Campi\u00f1a Domestica y Silvestre del Reino de Chile en 1744 - AHG.jpg|thumb|left|1744 engraving published in ''Relaci\u00f3n hist\u00f3rica del viaje a la Am\u00e9rica meridional''. The image shows cattle in the Chilean countryside including a square for cattle slaughter.]]\n\n===Trade===\n{{see also|Bourbon reforms}}\nIn the 17th century economy of the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]], Chile's husbandry and agriculture based economy had a peripheral role, contrasting to ore-rich districts like [[Potos\u00ed]] and the wealthy city of [[Lima]]. Husbandry products made up the bulk of Chilean exports to the rest of the viceroyalty. These products included [[suet]], [[charqui]] and leather. This trade made Chilean historian [[Benjam\u00edn Vicu\u00f1a Mackenna]] label the 17th century the ''century of suet'' (Spanish: Siglo del sebo).<ref name=pueblo>{{cite book |last1=Villalobos |first1=Sergio |last2=\u00c1vila Retamal|first2=Julio|last3=Sol |first3=Serrano |authorlink1=Sergio Villalobos |title=Historia del pueblo Chileno |volume=4 |url= |accessdate= |year=2000 |publisher=|location= |isbn=|language=Spanish|page=154}}</ref> Other products exported included dry fruits, mules, wines and minor amounts of copper.<ref name=pueblo/> Trade with Peru was controlled by merchants from Lima that not only managed also the trade with Chile and [[Panama]] but also enjoyed protection by the authorities in Lima.<ref name=villalobos1687/> In addition to the exports to coastal Peru Chile also exported products inland to [[Upper Peru]] through the port of [[Arica, Chile|Arica]].<ref name=pueblo/> Trade inside Chile was small since cities were tiny and [[Self-sufficiency|self-sufficient]].<ref name=pueblo/>\n\nDirect trade with Spain over the [[Straits of Magellan]] and [[Buenos Aires]] begun first in the 18th century constituting primarily an export route for gold, silver and copper from Chilean mining. By the same time Spains trade monopoly with its colonies was successively weakened by smugglers from England, France and United States.<ref name=salazarpinto16-17>Salazar & Pinto 2002, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\n===Alerce logging===\nGenerally the extraction of wood had little importance in colonial Chile but [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] and [[Valdivia]] were exceptions.<ref name=villaloboswood>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 225.</ref> These two areas exported planks to Peru.<ref name=villaloboswood/> With the [[Destruction of the Seven Cities|destruction of Valdivia]] in 1599 Chilo\u00e9 gained increased importance as the only locale that could supply the Vice royalty of Peru with ''[[Fitzroya]]'' wood.<ref name=torrejon/> In 1641 the first large shipment of ''Fitzroya'' wood left Chilo\u00e9.<ref name=torrejon>Torrej\u00f3n, Fernando; Cisternas, Marco; Alvial, Ingrid and Torres, Laura. 2011. [http://www.scielo.cl/pdf/magallania/v39n2/art06.pdf Consecuencias de la tala Madeira colonial en los bosques de alece de Chilo\u00e9, sur de Chile (Siglos XVI-XIX)*]. ''[[Magallania]]''. Vol. 39(2):75\u201395.</ref>\n\n===Shipbuilding===\nIn the 18th century the shipbuilding industry in [[Valdivia]], one of the city's main economic activities, reached its peak building numerous ships including [[frigate]]s.<ref name=Guarda45-47>Guarda 1973, pp. 45\u201347.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Isabel |first=Montt Pinto |authorlink= |title=Breve Historia de Valdivia |url= |accessdate= |year=1971 |edition= |publisher=Editorial Francisco de Aguirre |location=Buenos Aires-Santiago |isbn= |page=55}}</ref> Other shipyards of Chile included those of [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]] and [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]].<ref name=Leon>{{Citation\n| last  = Le\u00f3n S\u00e1enz\n| first = Jorge\n| title = Los astilleros y la indutria matitima en el Pac\u00edfico americano: Siglos XVI a XIX\n| journal = Di\u00e1logos, Revista Electr\u00f3nica de Historia\n| volume  = 10\n| issue   = 1\n| year    = 2009\n| pages   = 44\u201390\n| url     = http://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/index.php/dialogos/article/view/6128\n}}</ref> The Chilo\u00e9 shipyards constructed he bulk of the ships in Chile until the mid-18th century.<ref name=Leon/> In 1794 a new shipyards was established the mouth of [[Maule River]] (present day [[Constituci\u00f3n, Chile|Constituci\u00f3n]]).<ref name=Leon/> Despite some navigators expressing that Valdivia had better conditions than [[Guayaquil]] in Ecuador, this last port was the chief shipyard of the Spanish Empire in the Pacific.<ref name=Guarda45-47/><ref name=Leon/>\n\n==War and defense==\n\n===Arauco War===\n{{main|Arauco War}}\nIn 1550 Pedro de Valdivia, who aimed to control all of Chile to the [[Straits of Magellan]], traveled southward to conquer Mapuche territory.<ref name=villalobos98-99>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 98\u201399.</ref> Between 1550 and 1553 the Spanish founded several cities{{refn|group=\"note\"|These \"cities\" were often in fact more forts than cities.<ref name=MCLGuerraarauco/>}} in Mapuche lands including [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Valdivia]], [[Carahue|Imperial]], [[Villarrica, Chile|Villarrica]] and [[Angol]].<ref name=villalobos98-99/> The Spanish did also established the forts of [[Arauco, Chile|Arauco]], [[Pur\u00e9n]] and [[Tucapel]].<ref name=villalobos98-99/>\n\nFollowing these initial conquest the [[Arauco War]], a long period of intermittent war, between Mapuches and Spaniards broke out. A contributing factor was the lack a tradition of [[forced labour]] like the Andean [[mita (Inca)|mita]] among the Mapuches who largely refused to serve the Spanish.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo252-253>Bengoa 2003, pp. 252\u2013253.</ref> On the other hand, the Spanish, in particular those from [[Old Castile|Castile]] and [[Extremadura]], came from an extremely violent society.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo261>Bengoa 2003, p. 261.</ref> Since the Spanish arrival to the [[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|Araucan\u00eda]] in 1550 the Mapuches frequently laid siege to the Spanish cities in the 1550\u20131598 period.<ref name=MCLGuerraarauco>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-691.html\n| title = La Guerra de Arauco (1550\u20131656)\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = January 30, 2014\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> The war was mostly a [[low intensity conflict]].<ref name=Dillehay2007p335>Dillehay 2007, p. 335.</ref>\n\nA watershed event happened in 1598. That year a party of warriors from [[Pur\u00e9n]] were returning south from a raid against the surroundings of [[Chill\u00e1n]]. In their way back home they ambushed [[Mart\u00edn Garc\u00eda \u00d3\u00f1ez de Loyola]] and his troops that were sleeping without any night watch. It is not clear if they found the Spanish by accident or if they had followed them. The warriors, led by [[Pelantaro]], killed both the governor and all his troops.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo320-321>Bengoa 2003, pp. 320\u2013321.</ref>\n\nIn the years following the Battle of Curalaba a general uprising developed among the Mapuches and Huilliches. The Spanish cities of [[Angol]], [[Carahue|La Imperial]], [[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]], [[Santa Cruz de O\u00f1ez]], [[Valdivia]] and [[Villarrica, Chile|Villarrica]] were either destroyed or abandoned.<ref name=Villaloboes109>Villalobos ''et al.'' 1974, p. 109.</ref> Only [[Chill\u00e1n]] and [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]] resisted the Mapuche sieges and attacks.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo324-325>Bengoa 2003, pp. 324\u2013325.</ref> With the exception of [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] all the Chilean territory south of B\u00edo B\u00edo River became free of Spanish rule.<ref name=Villaloboes109/>\n\nAs the Spanish Empire faced a direct threat to its heartland in with the [[Reapers' War|Catalan Revolt]] of 1640 all resources were put crush the rebellion. With the Arauco War being a lengthy and [[Real Situado|costly]] conflict the Spanish crown ordered its authorities in Chile to sign [[Parliament of Quill\u00edn|a peace agreement]] with the Mapuche in order to concentrate the empire's resources in fighting the Catalans. This way the Mapuche obtained a peace treaty and a recognition on behalf of the crown in a case unique for any indigenous group in the Americas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9|author-link=Jos\u00e9 Bengoa |title= Columna de Jos\u00e9 Bengoa: Catalanes, Autonom\u00edas y Mapuche (s)|url=http://www.theclinic.cl/2017/10/04/columna-jose-bengoa-catalanes-autonomias-mapuche-s/ |work=[[The Clinic (newspaper)|The Clinic]] |location=|date=October 4, 2017 |access-date=October 21, 2017|language=Spanish }}</ref> This peace treaty did end the hostilities for a time, but they continued to flare up through the colonial era, most notably [[Mapuche uprising of 1655|in 1655]].\n\n===Pirates and corsairs===\n{{main|Coastal defence of colonial Chile}}\nIn Colonial times the [[Spanish Empire]] diverted significant resources to fortify the Chilean coast as consequence of Dutch and English raids.<ref name=MCLValcolonial>{{Cite journal| url = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-3522.html\n| title = Ingenier\u00eda Militar durante la Colonia\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = September 30, 2014\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1600 local Huilliche joined the Dutch [[Privateer|corsair]] [[Baltazar de Cordes]] to attack the Spanish settlement of [[Castro, Chile|Castro]].<ref name=Urbina>{{cite journal |url=http://www.memoriachilena.cl/archivos2/pdfs/mc0008625.pdf |title=La rebeli\u00f3n indigena de 1712: Los tributarios de Chilo\u00e9 contra la encomienda |journal=Tiempo y espacio |year=1990 | pages = 73\u201386 |volume=1 | issue =|accessdate=February 22, 2014 |last1=Urbina Burgos |first1=Rodolfo |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=MCLlaencomienda>{{Citation\n| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/temas/index.asp?id_ut=laencomienda.siglosxvi-xviii\n| title = La encomienda\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = January 30, 2014\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> While this was a sporadic attack the Spanish believed the Dutch could attempt to ally the Mapuches and establish a stronghold in southern Chile.<ref name=Clark2006>{{Cite thesis |last=Clark Berger |first=Eugene |title=Permanent war on Peru's periphery: Frontier identity and the politics of conflict in 17th century Chile |type=PhD |chapter= |url=http://etd.library.vanderbilt.edu/available/etd-07242006-180102/unrestricted/Dissertation.pdf |author= |year=2006 |publisher=[[Vanderbilt University]] |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |docket= |oclc= |page=13}}</ref> The Spanish knew of the Dutch plans to establish themselves at the ruins of Valdivia so they attempted to re-establish Spanish rule there before the Dutch arrived again.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo450-451>Bengoa 2003, pp. 450\u2013451.</ref> The Spanish attempts were thwarted in the 1630s when Mapuches did not allow the Spanish to pass by their territory.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo450-451/>\n\nThe [[Dutch occupation of Valdivia]] in 1643 caused great alarm among Spanish authorities and triggered the construction of the [[Valdivian Fort System]] that begun in 1645.<ref name=Kock>Robbert Kock [http://www.colonialvoyage.com/dutchchile.html The Dutch in Chili] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204718/http://www.colonialvoyage.com/dutchchile.html# |date=March 3, 2016 }} at coloniavoyage.com</ref><ref name=Kris>{{cite book|author=Kris E. Lane|title=Pillaging the Empire: Piracy in the Americas, 1500\u20131750|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=893J8RTsKjgC|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-3083-4|pages=88\u201392}}</ref>\n\nAs consequence of the [[Seven Years' War]] the Valdivian Fort System, a Spanish defensive complex in [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]], was updated and reinforced from 1764 onwards. Other vulnerable localities of colonial Chile such as [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]], [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez Islands]] and [[Valpara\u00edso]] were also made ready for an eventual English attack.<ref name=MEMCh>{{Citation\n| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-3522.html\n| title = Ingenier\u00eda Militar durante la Colonia\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| language =Spanish\n| accessdate =December 30, 2015\n}}</ref><ref name=MEMCh2>{{Citation\n| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-printer-94644.html\n| title = Lugares estrat\u00e9gicos\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| language =Spanish\n| accessdate =December 30, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nWith Spain and Great Britain at war again in the 1770s due to the [[American Revolutionary War]] local Spanish authorities in Chile received in 1779 the warning that a British fleet commanded by [[Edward Hughes (Royal Navy officer)|Edward Hughes]] was heading to Chilean coasts for an imminent attack. As concequence of this the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]] send economic aid to the garrisons at [[Valpara\u00edso]] and [[Valdivia]]. The suspected attack did however never happen. In late 1788 suspicion of British attack rose appeared once again, this time stemming from observations of ships off the coast of [[Coquimbo]].<ref name=Ossa2010>{{cite journal |last=Ossa Santa Cruz |first=Juan Luis |date=2010 |title=La criollizaci\u00f3n de un ej\u00e9rcito perif\u00e9rico, Chile, 1768\u20131810 |url=http://revistahistoria.uc.cl/estudios/2247/ |journal=[[Historia (history of the Americas journal)|Historia]] |volume=42 |issue=II |pages=413\u2013448 |access-date=January 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201133624/http://revistahistoria.uc.cl/estudios/2247/# |archive-date=February 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=Jos\u00e9 Bengoa|title=Historia de los antiguos mapuches del sur |url= |accessdate= |year=2003 |edition= |publisher=[[Catalonia (publisher)|Catalonia]] |location=Santiago |isbn=956-8303-02-2 |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last=Guarda |first=Gabriel |authorlink=Gabriel Guarda |title=La econom\u00eda de Chile Austral antes de la colonizaci\u00f3n alemana |url= |accessdate= |year=1973 |edition= |publisher=[[Universidad Austral de Chile]] |location=[[Valdivia]] |isbn= |page=|language=Spanish}}\n*[[Gabriel Salazar|Salazar, Gabriel]] (1985). ''Labradores, Peones y Proletarios'' (in Spanish) (3rd ed.). [[LOM Ediciones]]. {{ISBN|956-282-269-9}}.\n*Salazar, Gabriel; [[Julio Pinto|Pinto, Julio]] (2002). ''Historia contempor\u00e1nea de Chile III. La econom\u00eda: mercados empresarios y trabajadores'' (in Spanish). [[LOM Ediciones]]. {{ISBN|956-282-172-2}}.\n*{{cite book |last=Valenzuela M\u00e1rquez |first=Jaime |editor-last1=Gaune |editor-first1=Rafael |editor-last2=Lara |editor-first2=Mart\u00edn |title=Historias de racismo y discriminaci\u00f3n en Chile |publisher= |date=2009 |pages= |chapter=Esclavos mapuches. Para una historia del secuestro y deportaci\u00f3n de ind\u00edgenas en la colonia|isbn=|language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Villalobos |first1=Sergio|authorlink1=Sergio Villalobos |last2=Silva |first2=Osvaldo|last3=Silva |first3=Fernando|last4=Estelle |first4=Patricio  |title=Historia de Chile |url= |edition=14th |accessdate= |year=1974 |publisher=Editorial Universitaria|location=[[Santiago, Chile|Santiago de Chile]] |isbn=956-11-1163-2 |language=Spanish}}\n\n{{Spanish America}}\n{{Chile topics}}\n\n[[Category:Captaincy General of Chile]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{History of Chile}}\nIn Chilean [[historiography]], '''Colonial Chile''' ({{lang-es|link=no|la colonia}}) is the period from 1600 to 1810, beginning with the [[Destruction of the Seven Cities]] and ending with the onset of the [[Chilean War of Independence]]. During this time the Chilean heartland was ruled by [[Captaincy General of Chile]]. The period was characterized by a lengthy conflict between Spaniards and native [[Mapuche]]s known as the [[Arauco War]]. Colonial society was divided in distinct groups including [[Peninsulars]], [[Criollo people|Criollos]], [[Mestizo]]s, [[Indigenous peoples in South America|Indians]] and [[African Chilean|Black people]].\n\nRelative to other Spanish colonies Chile was a \"poor and dangerous\" place.<ref name=Hojman/>{{efn-ua|While not falling in the ''sensu stricto'' colonial period the inhabitants of Santiago in the mid-16th century were notoriously poorly dressed as result of a lack of supplies with some Spanish even resorting to dress with [[hide (skin)|hides]] from dogs, cats, [[South American sea lion|sea lions]] and [[South American fox|foxes]].<ref name=leon1991>{{cite book |last=Le\u00f3n |first=Leonardo|author-link=Leonardo Le\u00f3n |title=La merma de la sociadad ind\u00edgena en Chile central y la \u00faltima guerra de los promaucaes |url=http://www.memoriachilena.gob.cl/archivos2/pdfs/MC0012923.pdf |year=1991 |edition= |publisher=Institute of Amerindian Studies, University of St. Andrews |isbn=1873617003 |language=Spanish|pages=13\u201316}}<!--|accessdate=August 27, 2019 --></ref>}}\n\n==Society==\n\n===Societal groups===\n[[File:Baile del Santiago antiguo.jpg|thumb|300px|\"''Baile del Santiago antiguo''\" by [[Pedro Subercaseaux]]. Chile's colonial high society were made up by landowners and government officials.]]\nThe Chilean colonial society was based on a [[caste system]]. Local of [[Criollo people|criollo]]s (American born Spaniards) enjoyed privileges like the [[ownership]] of [[encomienda]]s (Indian labour jurisdictions) and were allowed to access some public charges like [[Corregidor (position)|corregidor]] or [[alf\u00e9rez]]. [[Mestizo]]s made up initially a small group but came with time to make up the bulk of Chilean society becoming more numerous than indigenous peoples.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Mestizos were not a homogeneous group and were judged more by appearance than by actual ancestry.<ref name=villalobos186>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 186.</ref> Indians enjoyed the lowest prestige among societal groups in colonial Chile, many of them were used as cheap labour in encomienda but their numbers decreased over time due to [[diseases]] and [[mestization]]. [[Pehuenche]]'s, [[Huilliche]]s and Mapuches living south of [[La Frontera, Chile|La Frontera]] were not part of the colonial society since they were outside the ''de facto'' borders of Chile.\n\nSpanish agriculture, centered on the hacienda, absorbed most of the scattered and declining indigenous populations of Central Chile.<ref name=migracioneslocales>{{Cite journal|title=Migraciones locales y asentamiento ind\u00edgena en las estancias espa\u00f1olas de Chile central, 1580-1650|journal=[[Historia (history of the Americas journal)|Historia]]|volume=49|issue=1|doi=10.4067/S0717-71942016000100004|url=https://scielo.conicyt.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0717-71942016000100004&script=sci_arttext#nb29|year=2016|language=Spanish|doi-access=free}}</ref> Thus populations that had previously lived apart in their own villages (''pueblo de indios'') from their Spanish masters begun to live in Spanish estancias.<ref name=migracioneslocales/> In Central Chile the dwindling population of [[Picunche]]s occurred in parallel to import of [[Slavery of Mapuches|Mapuche and Huilliche slaves]] from Araucan\u00eda and Chilo\u00e9,{{efn-ua|It is possible that slaves exported from Chilo\u00e9 included some few [[Chono]] and [[Poya people|Poyas]].<ref>{{Cite book|chapter=El pueblo chono: de vagabundo y pagano a cristiano y sedentario mestizado|journal=|url=http://www.turismocientifico.cl/admin/apps/filemanager/repository/%C3%A1reas%20del%20conocimiento/Poblamiento,%20historia%20y%20cultura/Antropologia/Etnias/Al%20Pueblo%20Chono.pdf|last=Urbina Burgos|first=Rodolfo|pages=325\u2013346|title=Orbis incognitvs: avisos y legados del Nuevo Mundo|year=2007|publisher=Universidad de Huelva|location=Huelva|ISBN=9788496826243|language=Spanish}}</ref>}} as well as the arrival of indigenous people from [[Peru]], [[Tucum\u00e1n]] and the transfer of encomienda [[Huarpe]]s from [[Cuyo (Argentina)|Cuyo]].<ref name=migracioneslocales/><ref name=villalobosHacienda2/> This mix of disparate populations cohabitating with the Spanish contributed to the loss of indigenous identities.<ref name=migracioneslocales/> \n\nFor many years, Spanish-descent settlers and religious orders imported African slaves to the country, which in the early 19th century constituted 1.5% of the national population.<ref>{{Citation\n| last      = Mellafe\n| first     = Rolando\n| title     = La introducci\u00f3n de la esclavitud negra en Chile: Tr\u00e1fico y rutas\n| publisher = Universidad de Chile\n| place     = Santiago de Chile\n| year      = 1959\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> Despite this, the [[Afro-Chilean]] population was negligible, reaching a height of only 2,500 \u2013 or 0.1% of the total population \u2013 during the colonial period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mazinger.sisib.uchile.cl/repositorio/lb/ciencias_quimicas_y_farmaceuticas/medinae/ |title=Elementos de Salud P\u00fablica, section 5.2.6 |publisher=University of Chile |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090916211140/http://mazinger.sisib.uchile.cl/repositorio/lb/ciencias_quimicas_y_farmaceuticas/medinae/ |archivedate=September 16, 2009 }}</ref> While a minority black slaves had a special status due to their high cost of import<ref name=Villalobos254>Villalobos ''et al.'' 1974, p. 254.</ref> and maintenance.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Black slaves were often used as [[housekeeper (domestic worker)|housekeepers]] and other posts of confidence.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}} Peninsulares, Spaniards born in Spain, were a rather small group in late colonial times, some of them came as government officials and some other as merchants. Their role in high government positions in Chile led to resentment among local criollos.<ref name=villalobos274>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 274.</ref> Mixing of different groups was not uncommon although marriage between members of the different groups was rare.\n\nDuring late colonial times new migration pulses took off leading to large numbers of [[Basque people]] settling in Chile mingling with landowning criollos, forming a new upper class.<ref name=villalobos257-259>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 257\u2013259.</ref> Scholar Luis Thayer Ojeda estimates that during the 17th and 18th centuries fully 45% of all immigrants in [[History of Chile|Chile]] were Basques.<ref>William A. Douglass, Jon Bilbao (2005). \"''[https://books.google.com/books?id=8KzfK1QwxDIC&pg=PA81 Amerikanuak: Basques in the New World]''\". [[University of Nevada Press]]. p. 81. {{ISBN|0-87417-625-5}}</ref> Compared to other Spanish colonies in the Americas the proportion of women among and merchants among Spanish immigrants to Chile were lower and the proportion of non-Spanish immigrants (e.g. French, Irish) higher.<ref name=Hojman>{{Citation\n| last  = Hojman\n| first = David E.\n| title = The Dutch invasion of colonial Chiloe and early Chilean exceptionalism: A critical juncture and counterfactuals approach\n| pages   = 1\u201348\n| url     = https://www.liv.ac.uk/media/livacuk/schoolofmanagement/docs/drive/The,Dutch,invasion,of,colonial,Chiloe,and,early,Chilean,exceptionalism.pdf\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1812, the Diocese of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Concepci\u00f3n|Concepci\u00f3n]] conducted a census to the south of the [[Maule river]]; however, this did not include the indigenous population \u2013 at that time estimated at 8,000 people \u2013 nor the inhabitants of the province of Chilo\u00e9. It put the total population at 210,567, of which 86.1% was native Spaniards and 10% were Indian, with a remaining 3.7% of Africans, [[mulatto]]s, and mestizo descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ine.cl/canales/usuarios/cedoc_online/censos/pdf/censo_1813.pdf |title=INE \u2013 Censo de 1813. Introducci\u00f3n |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2011-09-22}}</ref> Other estimates in the late 17th century indicate that the population reached a maximum total of 152,000, consisting of 72% whites and mestizos, 18% Indians, and 10% blacks and mulattos.<ref>[http://www.glamorama.cl/medio/articulo/0,0,38035857_152309033_151837148,00.html Icarito \u2013 La Colonia:Poblaci\u00f3n y sociedad]{{dead link|date=December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Sex and marriage===\nIndigenous women in the colonial society were noted, from a Spanish point of view, for their sexual liberalism and engaged often sexually with men from other ethnicities.<ref name=privada>{{Citation\n| last  = Retamal \u00c1.\n| first = Julio\n| chapter = Fidelidad conyugal en el Chile colonial\n| editor-last  = Sagredo\n| editor-first = Rafael\n| editor-last2  = Gazmuri\n| editor-first2 = Cristi\u00e1n\n| title = Historia de la vida privada en Chile\n| volume = 1\n| pages  = 53\u201363\n| publisher = Aguilar Chilena de Ediciones\n| place = Santiago de Chile\n| publication-date = 2005\n| edition = 4th\n| isbn = 956-239-337-2\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> The same was true for the black slaves who due to their \"many\" intercourses with other groups were strictly prohibited by law to engage in sexual activities with other ethnicities in order to avoid the proliferation of black individuals.<ref name=privada/>\n\n16th century Spaniards are known to have been pessimistic about marriage.<ref name=privada/> Many of the initial [[conquistador]]es had left their wives in Spain and engaged in [[adultery]] in Chile.<ref name=privada/> Examples of this is [[Pedro de Valdivia]] who held [[In\u00e9s de Su\u00e1rez]] as lover.<ref name=privada/> Adultery was explicitly forbidden for Catholics and the [[Council of Trent]] (1545\u20131563) made the climate prone for accusations of adultery.<ref name=privada/> Over the course of the 16th, 17th and 18th centuries marital fidelity increased in Chile.<ref name=privada/>\n\n==Political organization==\n{{see also|Captaincy General of Chile|Governorate of Chilo\u00e9|Intendancy of Chilo\u00e9}}\nThe government of Chile or ''Nueva Toledo'' was created by Emperor [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] in 1534 and placed under the governorship of [[Diego de Almagro]]. It ran south from 14\u00b0 S to 25\u00b0 S latitude, as far south as present-day [[Taltal]].  ''[[Capitan\u00eda General de Chile]]'', or ''Gobernaci\u00f3n de Chile'', remained a colony of the Spanish Empire until 1818 when it declared itself independent.  In the mid Eighteenth Century, the [[Bourbon Reforms#Spanish America|Bourbon administrative reforms]] divided Chile into [[intendencias]] (provinces) and further into ''partidos'' (counties) which were also known by the older term of ''corregimientos''. The ''partidos'' were further divided into ''distritos'' (districts) akin to Chile's modern [[Communes of Chile|communes]].<ref name=\"Cobos\">{{Cite book|author=Cobos, Mar\u00eda Teresa |year=1989 |title=La divisi\u00f3n pol\u00edtico-administrativa de Chile, 1541\u20131811 |language=es|location=Valpara\u00edso, Chile |publisher=Instituto de Historia, Vicerrector\u00eda Acad\u00e9mica, Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de Valpara\u00edso |oclc=30686100}}</ref> In 1786 two intendencias were created: Santiago and [[Concepci\u00f3n Province, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]. By the end of the 18th century, Santiago was divided into thirteen ''partidos''.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Carvallo y Goyeneche, Vicente |authorlink=Vicente Carvallo y Goyeneche |year=1875 |title=Descripci\u00f3n Hist\u00f3rico Geograf\u00eda del Reino de Chile (part 3)|language=es|journal=Colecci\u00f3n de Historiadores de Chile y documentos relativos a la Historia Nacional |volume=10 |publisher=Sociedad Chilena de Historia y Geograf\u00eda |location=Santiago de Chile |url=http://www.memoriachilena.cl/archivos2/pdfs/MC0008930.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007230529/http://www.memoriachilena.cl/archivos2/pdfs/MC0008930.pdf |archivedate=October 7, 2007 |url-status=live}} manuscript 1795.</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" align=\"center\" width=60%\n|- bgcolor=\"#ececec\"\n! ''Partido''!! [[Administrative centre]]\n|-\n|Santiago\n|[[Santiago|Ciudad de Santiago del Nuevo Extremo]]\n|-\n|Copiap\u00f3\n|[[Copiap\u00f3|Villa de San Francisco de la Selva]]\n|-\n|Huasco\n|[[Freirina|Villa de Santa Rosa del Huasco]]\n|-\n|Coquimbo\n|[[La Serena, Chile|Ciudad de San Bartolom\u00e9 de la Serena]]\n|-\n|Cuzc\u00faz\n|[[Illapel|Villa de San Rafael de Rozas]]\n|-\n|Quillota\n|[[Quillota|Villa de San Mart\u00edn de la Concha]]\n|-\n|Valpara\u00edso\n|[[Valpara\u00edso|Puerto de Valpara\u00edso]]\n|-\n|Aconcagua\n|[[San Felipe, Chile|Villa de San Felipe el Real]]\n|-\n|Melipilla\n|[[Melipilla|Villa de San Jos\u00e9 de Logro\u00f1o]]\n|-\n|Rancagua\n|[[Rancagua|Villa de Santa Cruz de Triana]]\n|-\n|Colchagua\n|[[San Fernando, Chile|Villa de San Fernando el Real de Tinguiririca]]\n|-\n|Curic\u00f3\n|[[Curic\u00f3|Villa de San Jos\u00e9 de la Buenavista]]\n|-\n|Maule\n|[[Talca|Villa de San Agust\u00edn de Talca]]\n|-\n|}\n\nThe intendencia of Concepcion had six ''partidos'': Cauquenes, Chill\u00e1n, Itata, Rere, Laja, and Puchacay. A third intendencia, Coquimbo was created in 1810. The area of [[Chilo\u00e9 Province|Chilo\u00e9]] may be considered a fourth intendencia, but instead of reporting to the governor/capitain it reported directly to the viceroy, beginning in 1777.<ref name=\"Cobos\" /><ref>{{Cite book|author=Encina, Francisco Antonio|year=1952 |title=Historia de Chile: Desde la prehistoria hasta 1891 |location=Santiago |language=es|edition=second | publisher=Nascimento| volume=IV |page= 643}}</ref> The ''intendencia'', ''partido'' and ''distrito'' system was replaced in 1822 with ''departamentos'', ''distritos'' and ''cabildos''.\n\n==Labor forms==\n\n===Encomienda===\nBeyond subsistence the 16th century economy of Chile was oriented towards large-scale production. Spanish colonizers used large amounts of indigenous labour following the slave labour system used in the [[sugar cane]] plantations of the [[Mediterranean islands]] and [[Macaronesia]]. This system of labour successively killed the production base leading to the imposition of the [[encomienda|encomienda system]] by the Spanish Crown in order to prevent excesses. In Chile Spanish settlers managed to continue to exploit indigenous labour under slave like conditions despite the implementation of the encomienda. Rich Spanish settlers had over time to face opposition to their mode of production by [[Jesuit]]s, Spanish officials and indigenous [[Mapuche]]s.<ref name=GZ23-25>Salazar 1985, pp. 23\u201325.</ref>\n\nOver the course of the 17th century the indigenous population of Chile declined making the [[encomienda]]s less and less important.<ref name=villalobosHacienda>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 160\u2013165.</ref> Chilean encomenderos who had encomiendas in [[Cuyo (Argentina)|Cuyo]], across the Andes, introduced to Chile indigenous [[Huarpe people|Huarpes]] who they hired to other Spanish without encomiendas.<ref name=villalobosHacienda2>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 166\u2013170.</ref>\n\nThe encomienda system was abolished in 1782 in [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago|Chilo\u00e9]] and in 1789 in the rest of Chile and in 1791 in the whole Spanish Empire.<ref name=Urbina/><ref name=llanquihue>{{in lang|es}} [http://www.diariollanquihue.cl/prontus4_nots/site/artic/20070728/pags/20070728230653.html La rebeli\u00f3n huilliche de 1712] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203011346/http://www.diariollanquihue.cl/prontus4_nots/site/artic/20070728/pags/20070728230653.html |date=December 3, 2013 }} ''[[El Llanquihue]]''. Puplished in July 29, 2007. Retrieved 2012-05-26.</ref><ref name=MCLlaencomienda/><ref name=villalobos>[[Sergio Villalobos|Villalobos, Sergio]]; Silva, Osvaldo; Silva, Fernando and Estelle, Patricio. 1974. ''Historia De Chile''. [[Editorial Universitaria]], Chile. p 237.</ref>\n\n===Inquilinaje===\n{{main|inquilino}}\n\n===Formal slavery===\n{{see also|Afro-Chilean|Slavery of Mapuches|Atlantic slave trade}}\nThe Spanish were familiar with the institution of slavery. In the [[Mediterranean islands]] and [[Macaronesia]] the Spanish and Portuguese had a slave labour system used in [[sugar cane]] plantations.<ref name=GZ23-25/> In the [[Iberian peninsula]] slavery was declining did still occur in the 16th century.<ref name=MCLesclavitud>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-100668.html\n| title = La esclavitud negra en Chile (1536\u20131823)\n| work  = [[Memoria Chilena]]\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = May 30, 2015\n| language = Spanish\n| postscript = .\n}}</ref> The import of black slaves into Chile was a response to a long-term population decline among indigenous peoples.  Slavery was a legal labour form in Chile from 1536 to 1823 but it was never the dominant way of arranging labour. Slavery of black people bloomed from 1580 to 1660. The end of the boom is associated to the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] and Portugal's loss of several slave trading posts in Africa.<ref name=MCLesclavitud/>\n\nFormal slavery of indigenous people was prohibited by the Spanish Crown. The 1598\u20131604 [[Mapuche]] uprising that ended with the [[Destruction of the Seven Cities]] made the Spanish in 1608 declare slavery legal for those Mapuches caught in war.<ref name=Valenzuela231-233/> Rebelling Mapuches were considered Christian [[Apostasy|apostates]] and could therefore be enslaved according to the church teachings of the day.<ref>{{cite book |last=Foerster |first=Rolf |date=1993 |title=Introducci\u00f3n a la religiosidad mapuche |url= |location= |publisher=[[Editorial universitaria]] |page=21 |language=Spanish |isbn= |access-date= }}</ref> This legal change formalized Mapuche slavery that was already occurring at the time, with captured Mapuches being treated as property in the way that they were bought and sold among the Spanish. Legalisation made Spanish [[slave raiding]] increasingly common in the [[Arauco War]].<ref name=Valenzuela231-233>Valenzuela M\u00e1rquez 2009, p. 231\u2013233</ref> Mapuche slaves were exported north to [[La Serena, Chile|La Serena]] and [[Lima]].<ref name=Valenzuela234236/> Slavery for Mapuches \"caught in war\" was abolished in 1683 after decades of legal attempts by the Spanish Crown to suppress it. By that time free mestizo labour had become significantly cheaper than ownership of slaves which made [[Mario G\u00f3ngora]] in 1966 conclude that economic factors were behind the abolition.<ref name=Valenzuela234236>Valenzuela M\u00e1rquez 2009, pp. 234\u2013236</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n{{Location map+|Chile|float=right|width=300|caption=Location Spanish settlements within the modern boundaries of Chile in late colonial times. Color of dots shows the date since the settlements have been in continous existence. 16th century: red dots. 17th century: blue dots. 18th century: yellow dots. Red circles shows areas of indigenous resistance to Spanish penetration by the late 18th century.|places=\n<!-- North-East-->\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-18.483333 |long=-70.333333 |label=[[Arica]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-27.366389 |long=-70.333056 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-28.466389 |long=-71.219167 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-29.9 |long=-71.25 |label=[[La Serena|La Serena]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-31.633333 |long=-71.166667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.251389 |long=-70.931389 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.45 |long=-71.216667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.75 |long=-70.723889 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-32.833333 |long=-70.616667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.05 |long=-71.616667 |label=[[Valpara\u00edso]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.316667 |long=-71.416667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-33.45 |long=-70.666667 |label=[[Santiago]]|position=right|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-34.166667 |long=-70.75 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-34.583333 |long=-70.983333 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-34.983333 |long=-71.233333 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-35.433333 |long=-71.666667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.623889 |long=-72.135833 |label=|position=right|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-36.733333 |long=-72.983333 |label=[[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.25 |long=-73.316667 |label=|position=left|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-37.5 |long=-72.666667 |label=|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~\n |Chile\n |label=[[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|Araucan\u00eda]]\n |relief=yes \n |lat=-38.80582 \n |long=-72.601265\n |position=left\n |width=100\n |label_width=8\n |float=right\n |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=40\n |caption=Locationx\n}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-39.890556 |long=-73.393333 |label=[[Valdivia]]|position=left|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~\n |Chile\n |label=[[Futahuillimapu]]\n |relief=yes \n |lat=-40.90582 \n |long=-73.521265\n |position=left\n |width=100\n |label_width=8\n |float=right\n |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg\n |marksize=25\n |caption=Locationx\n}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-40.5725 |long=-73.135278 |label=[[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]]|position=right|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.7712 |long=-73.1275 |label=|position=right|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.866667 |long=-73.833333 |label=[[Ancud]]|position=left|mark=Yellow pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-41.745833 |long=-73.706389 |label=|position=right|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{Location map~|Chile|lat=-42.466667 |long=-73.8 |label=[[Castro, Chile|Castro]]|position=left|mark=Red pog.svg}}\n}}\n{{main|Economic history of Chile}}\nThe [[Destruction of the Seven Cities|collapse of the Spanish cities]] in the south following the [[battle of Curalaba]] (1598) meant for the Spaniards the loss of both the main gold districts and the largest indigenous labour sources.<ref name=salazarpinto>Salazar & Pinto 2002, p. 15.</ref> After those dramatic years the colony of Chile became concentrated in the [[Zona Central, Chile|central valley]] which became increasingly populated, explored and economically exploited. Following a tendency common in the whole [[Spanish America]] [[hacienda]]s were formed as the economy moved away from mining and into agriculture and husbandry.<ref name=villalobosHacienda/>\n\nIn the 1650\u20131800 period the Chilean lower classes grew considerably in size.<ref name=GZ49>Salazar 1985, p. 49.</ref> To deal with the poor and landless population a policy of founding cities<ref group=\"note\">These cities were often in fact more of villages or towns due to their size.</ref> and granting lands in their surroundings was implemented.<ref name=GZ49/> From 1730 to 1820 a large number of farmers settled in the outskirts of old cities or formed new cities.<ref>Salazar 1985, p. 58.</ref> Settling as a farmer in the outskirts of old cities ([[La Serena, Chile|La Serena]], [[Valpara\u00edso]], [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]] and [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]]) was overall more popular than joining a new city since it secured a larger consumer market for agricultural products.<ref>Salazar 1985, p. 52.</ref> Chilean [[hacienda]]s ([[latifundium|latifundia]]) engaged little in the supply of Chilean cities but focused on international exports for revenues.<ref>Salazar 1985, p. 88.</ref>\n\nHaciendas of central Chile are believed to had become labour-saturated by 1780 generating an \"excess\" population that could not be incorporated into their economy.<ref name=GZ154>Salazar 1985, p. 153\u2013154.</ref> Some of this population settled in the outskirts of larger cities while other migrated to the mining districts of [[Norte Chico, Chile|Norte Chico]].<ref name=GZ154/>\n\n===Agriculture===\n{{see also|Chilean wheat cycle}}\n{{rquote|right|without Chile, Lima would not exist|Viceroy [[Jos\u00e9 de Armend\u00e1riz, 1st Marquis of Castelfuerte|Jos\u00e9 de Armend\u00e1riz]] in 1736<ref>Quoted in [[Diego Barros Arana]]'s ''Hist\u00f3ria general de Chile'', Vol. 16 (Santiago, 1884\u20131902), p. 74.</ref>}}\nChile began exporting cereals to [[Peru]] in 1687 when Peru was struck by both [[1687 Peru earthquake|an earthquake]] and a [[stem rust]] epidemic.<ref name=villalobos1687>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 155\u2013160.</ref> Chilean soil and climatic conditions were better for cereal production than those of Peru and Chilean wheat was cheaper and of better quality than Peruvian wheat.<ref name=villalobos1687/><ref name=collier>Collier, Simon and Sater William F. 2004. ''A History of Chile: 1808\u20132002'' [[Cambridge University Press]]. p. 10.</ref> According to historians [[Sergio Villalobos|Villalobos]] ''et al''. the 1687 events were only the detonant factor for exports to start.<ref name=villalobos1687/> The [[Chilean Central Valley]], La Serena and Concepci\u00f3n were the districts that came to be involved in cereal export to Peru.<ref name=villalobos1687/> It should be pointed out that compared with the 19th century the area cultivated with wheat was very small and production modest.<ref name=collier/>\n\nInitially Chilean [[Latifundium|latifundia]] could not meet the wheat demand due to a labour shortage, so had to incorporate [[Temporary work|temporal workers]] in addition to the permanent staff. Another response by the latifundia to labour shortages was to act as merchants buying wheat produced by independent farmers or from farmers that hired land. In the period 1700 to 1850 this second option was overall more lucrative.<ref>Salazar 1985, pp. 40\u201341</ref>\n\nThe 1687 Peru earthquake also ended a Peruvian wine-boom as the earthquake destroyed [[wine cellar]]s and mud containers used for wine storage.<ref name=Lacoste>{{Citation\n| last  = Lacoste\n| first = Pablo\n| title = La vid y el vino en Am\u00e9rica del Sur: el desplazamiento de los polos vitivin\u00edcolas (siglos XVI al XX)\n| journal = [[Revista Universum]]\n| volume  = 19\n| issue   = 2\n| year    = 2004\n| pages   = 62\u201393\n| url     = http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-23762004000200005&script=sci_arttext&tlng=es\n| doi=10.4067/s0718-23762004000200005\n| doi-access= free\n}}\n\n[http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-23762004000200005&script=sci_arttext&tlng=es ]</ref> The gradual decline of Peruvian wine even caused Peru to import some wine from Chile as it happened in 1795 when Lima imported 5.000 troves (Spanish: ''botijas'') from [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]] in southern Chile.<ref name=Lacoste/><ref name=pozo2>{{Citation\n| last1  = del Pozo\n| first1 = Jos\u00e9\n| lastauthoramp = yes\n| title     = Historia del vino chileno\n| publisher = [[Editorial Universitaria]]\n| year    = 2004\n| pages   = 35\u201345\n}}</ref> This particular export showed the emergence of Chile relative to Peru as a wine-making region.<ref name=Lacoste/>\n\n===Mining===\nCompared to the 16th and 18th centuries Chilean mining activity in the 17th century was very limited.<ref name=villalobos17thmining>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 168.</ref> Chile saw an unprecedented revival of its mining activity in the 18th century with annual gold production rising from 400 to 1000&nbsp;kg over the course of the century and the silver annual production rising from 1000 to 5000&nbsp;kg in the same interval.<ref name=villalobosMining>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 226\u2013227.</ref>\n\n[[File:Campi\u00f1a Domestica y Silvestre del Reino de Chile en 1744 - AHG.jpg|thumb|left|1744 engraving published in ''Relaci\u00f3n hist\u00f3rica del viaje a la Am\u00e9rica meridional''. The image shows cattle in the Chilean countryside including a square for cattle slaughter.]]\n\n===Trade===\n{{see also|Bourbon reforms}}\nIn the 17th century economy of the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]], Chile's husbandry and agriculture based economy had a peripheral role, contrasting to ore-rich districts like [[Potos\u00ed]] and the wealthy city of [[Lima]]. Husbandry products made up the bulk of Chilean exports to the rest of the viceroyalty. These products included [[suet]], [[charqui]] and leather. This trade made Chilean historian [[Benjam\u00edn Vicu\u00f1a Mackenna]] label the 17th century the ''century of suet'' (Spanish: Siglo del sebo).<ref name=pueblo>{{cite book |last1=Villalobos |first1=Sergio |last2=\u00c1vila Retamal|first2=Julio|last3=Sol |first3=Serrano |authorlink1=Sergio Villalobos |title=Historia del pueblo Chileno |volume=4 |url= |accessdate= |year=2000 |publisher=|location= |isbn=|language=Spanish|page=154}}</ref> Other products exported included dry fruits, mules, wines and minor amounts of copper.<ref name=pueblo/> Trade with Peru was controlled by merchants from Lima that not only managed also the trade with Chile and [[Panama]] but also enjoyed protection by the authorities in Lima.<ref name=villalobos1687/> In addition to the exports to coastal Peru Chile also exported products inland to [[Upper Peru]] through the port of [[Arica, Chile|Arica]].<ref name=pueblo/> Trade inside Chile was small since cities were tiny and [[Self-sufficiency|self-sufficient]].<ref name=pueblo/>\n\nDirect trade with Spain over the [[Straits of Magellan]] and [[Buenos Aires]] begun first in the 18th century constituting primarily an export route for gold, silver and copper from Chilean mining. By the same time Spains trade monopoly with its colonies was successively weakened by smugglers from England, France and United States.<ref name=salazarpinto16-17>Salazar & Pinto 2002, pp. 16\u201317.</ref>\n\n===Alerce logging===\nGenerally the extraction of wood had little importance in colonial Chile but [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] and [[Valdivia]] were exceptions.<ref name=villaloboswood>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, p. 225.</ref> These two areas exported planks to Peru.<ref name=villaloboswood/> With the [[Destruction of the Seven Cities|destruction of Valdivia]] in 1599 Chilo\u00e9 gained increased importance as the only locale that could supply the Vice royalty of Peru with ''[[Fitzroya]]'' wood.<ref name=torrejon/> In 1641 the first large shipment of ''Fitzroya'' wood left Chilo\u00e9.<ref name=torrejon>Torrej\u00f3n, Fernando; Cisternas, Marco; Alvial, Ingrid and Torres, Laura. 2011. [http://www.scielo.cl/pdf/magallania/v39n2/art06.pdf Consecuencias de la tala Madeira colonial en los bosques de alece de Chilo\u00e9, sur de Chile (Siglos XVI-XIX)*]. ''[[Magallania]]''. Vol. 39(2):75\u201395.</ref>\n\n===Shipbuilding===\nIn the 18th century the shipbuilding industry in [[Valdivia]], one of the city's main economic activities, reached its peak building numerous ships including [[frigate]]s.<ref name=Guarda45-47>Guarda 1973, pp. 45\u201347.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Isabel |first=Montt Pinto |authorlink= |title=Breve Historia de Valdivia |url= |accessdate= |year=1971 |edition= |publisher=Editorial Francisco de Aguirre |location=Buenos Aires-Santiago |isbn= |page=55}}</ref> Other shipyards of Chile included those of [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]] and [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]].<ref name=Leon>{{Citation\n| last  = Le\u00f3n S\u00e1enz\n| first = Jorge\n| title = Los astilleros y la indutria matitima en el Pac\u00edfico americano: Siglos XVI a XIX\n| journal = Di\u00e1logos, Revista Electr\u00f3nica de Historia\n| volume  = 10\n| issue   = 1\n| year    = 2009\n| pages   = 44\u201390\n| url     = http://revistas.ucr.ac.cr/index.php/dialogos/article/view/6128\n}}</ref> The Chilo\u00e9 shipyards constructed he bulk of the ships in Chile until the mid-18th century.<ref name=Leon/> In 1794 a new shipyards was established the mouth of [[Maule River]] (present day [[Constituci\u00f3n, Chile|Constituci\u00f3n]]).<ref name=Leon/> Despite some navigators expressing that Valdivia had better conditions than [[Guayaquil]] in Ecuador, this last port was the chief shipyard of the Spanish Empire in the Pacific.<ref name=Guarda45-47/><ref name=Leon/>\n\n==War and defense==\n\n===Arauco War===\n{{main|Arauco War}}\nIn 1550 Pedro de Valdivia, who aimed to control all of Chile to the [[Straits of Magellan]], traveled southward to conquer Mapuche territory.<ref name=villalobos98-99>Villalobos ''et al''. 1974, pp. 98\u201399.</ref> Between 1550 and 1553 the Spanish founded several cities{{refn|group=\"note\"|These \"cities\" were often in fact more forts than cities.<ref name=MCLGuerraarauco/>}} in Mapuche lands including [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Valdivia]], [[Carahue|Imperial]], [[Villarrica, Chile|Villarrica]] and [[Angol]].<ref name=villalobos98-99/> The Spanish did also established the forts of [[Arauco, Chile|Arauco]], [[Pur\u00e9n]] and [[Tucapel]].<ref name=villalobos98-99/>\n\nFollowing these initial conquest the [[Arauco War]], a long period of intermittent war, between Mapuches and Spaniards broke out. A contributing factor was the lack a tradition of [[forced labour]] like the Andean [[mita (Inca)|mita]] among the Mapuches who largely refused to serve the Spanish.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo252-253>Bengoa 2003, pp. 252\u2013253.</ref> On the other hand, the Spanish, in particular those from [[Old Castile|Castile]] and [[Extremadura]], came from an extremely violent society.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo261>Bengoa 2003, p. 261.</ref> Since the Spanish arrival to the [[Araucan\u00eda (historic region)|Araucan\u00eda]] in 1550 the Mapuches frequently laid siege to the Spanish cities in the 1550\u20131598 period.<ref name=MCLGuerraarauco>{{Cite journal| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-691.html\n| title = La Guerra de Arauco (1550\u20131656)\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = January 30, 2014\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> The war was mostly a [[low intensity conflict]].<ref name=Dillehay2007p335>Dillehay 2007, p. 335.</ref>\n\nA watershed event happened in 1598. That year a party of warriors from [[Pur\u00e9n]] were returning south from a raid against the surroundings of [[Chill\u00e1n]]. In their way back home they ambushed [[Mart\u00edn Garc\u00eda \u00d3\u00f1ez de Loyola]] and his troops that were sleeping without any night watch. It is not clear if they found the Spanish by accident or if they had followed them. The warriors, led by [[Pelantaro]], killed both the governor and all his troops.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo320-321>Bengoa 2003, pp. 320\u2013321.</ref>\n\nIn the years following the Battle of Curalaba a general uprising developed among the Mapuches and Huilliches. The Spanish cities of [[Angol]], [[Carahue|La Imperial]], [[Osorno, Chile|Osorno]], [[Santa Cruz de O\u00f1ez]], [[Valdivia]] and [[Villarrica, Chile|Villarrica]] were either destroyed or abandoned.<ref name=Villaloboes109>Villalobos ''et al.'' 1974, p. 109.</ref> Only [[Chill\u00e1n]] and [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]] resisted the Mapuche sieges and attacks.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo324-325>Bengoa 2003, pp. 324\u2013325.</ref> With the exception of [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]] all the Chilean territory south of B\u00edo B\u00edo River became free of Spanish rule.<ref name=Villaloboes109/>\n\nAs the Spanish Empire faced a direct threat to its heartland in with the [[Reapers' War|Catalan Revolt]] of 1640 all resources were put crush the rebellion. With the Arauco War being a lengthy and [[Real Situado|costly]] conflict the Spanish crown ordered its authorities in Chile to sign [[Parliament of Quill\u00edn|a peace agreement]] with the Mapuche in order to concentrate the empire's resources in fighting the Catalans. This way the Mapuche obtained a peace treaty and a recognition on behalf of the crown in a case unique for any indigenous group in the Americas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9|author-link=Jos\u00e9 Bengoa |title= Columna de Jos\u00e9 Bengoa: Catalanes, Autonom\u00edas y Mapuche (s)|url=http://www.theclinic.cl/2017/10/04/columna-jose-bengoa-catalanes-autonomias-mapuche-s/ |work=[[The Clinic (newspaper)|The Clinic]] |location=|date=October 4, 2017 |access-date=October 21, 2017|language=Spanish }}</ref> This peace treaty did end the hostilities for a time, but they continued to flare up through the colonial era, most notably [[Mapuche uprising of 1655|in 1655]].\n\n===Pirates and corsairs===\n{{main|Coastal defence of colonial Chile}}\nIn Colonial times the [[Spanish Empire]] diverted significant resources to fortify the Chilean coast as consequence of Dutch and English raids.<ref name=MCLValcolonial>{{Cite journal| url = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-3522.html\n| title = Ingenier\u00eda Militar durante la Colonia\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = September 30, 2014\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1600 local Huilliche joined the Dutch [[Privateer|corsair]] [[Baltazar de Cordes]] to attack the Spanish settlement of [[Castro, Chile|Castro]].<ref name=Urbina>{{cite journal |url=http://www.memoriachilena.cl/archivos2/pdfs/mc0008625.pdf |title=La rebeli\u00f3n indigena de 1712: Los tributarios de Chilo\u00e9 contra la encomienda |journal=Tiempo y espacio |year=1990 | pages = 73\u201386 |volume=1 | issue =|accessdate=February 22, 2014 |last1=Urbina Burgos |first1=Rodolfo |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=MCLlaencomienda>{{Citation\n| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/temas/index.asp?id_ut=laencomienda.siglosxvi-xviii\n| title = La encomienda\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| publisher  = [[Biblioteca Nacional de Chile]]\n| accessdate = January 30, 2014\n| language = Spanish\n}}</ref> While this was a sporadic attack the Spanish believed the Dutch could attempt to ally the Mapuches and establish a stronghold in southern Chile.<ref name=Clark2006>{{Cite thesis |last=Clark Berger |first=Eugene |title=Permanent war on Peru's periphery: Frontier identity and the politics of conflict in 17th century Chile |type=PhD |chapter= |url=http://etd.library.vanderbilt.edu/available/etd-07242006-180102/unrestricted/Dissertation.pdf |author= |year=2006 |publisher=[[Vanderbilt University]] |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |docket= |oclc= |page=13}}</ref> The Spanish knew of the Dutch plans to establish themselves at the ruins of Valdivia so they attempted to re-establish Spanish rule there before the Dutch arrived again.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo450-451>Bengoa 2003, pp. 450\u2013451.</ref> The Spanish attempts were thwarted in the 1630s when Mapuches did not allow the Spanish to pass by their territory.<ref name=BengoaAntiguo450-451/>\n\nThe [[Dutch occupation of Valdivia]] in 1643 caused great alarm among Spanish authorities and triggered the construction of the [[Valdivian Fort System]] that begun in 1645.<ref name=Kock>Robbert Kock [http://www.colonialvoyage.com/dutchchile.html The Dutch in Chili] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303204718/http://www.colonialvoyage.com/dutchchile.html# |date=March 3, 2016 }} at coloniavoyage.com</ref><ref name=Kris>{{cite book|author=Kris E. Lane|title=Pillaging the Empire: Piracy in the Americas, 1500\u20131750|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=893J8RTsKjgC|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-3083-4|pages=88\u201392}}</ref>\n\nAs consequence of the [[Seven Years' War]] the Valdivian Fort System, a Spanish defensive complex in [[Zona Sur|southern Chile]], was updated and reinforced from 1764 onwards. Other vulnerable localities of colonial Chile such as [[Chilo\u00e9 Archipelago]], [[Concepci\u00f3n, Chile|Concepci\u00f3n]], [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez Islands]] and [[Valpara\u00edso]] were also made ready for an eventual English attack.<ref name=MEMCh>{{Citation\n| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-article-3522.html\n| title = Ingenier\u00eda Militar durante la Colonia\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| language =Spanish\n| accessdate =December 30, 2015\n}}</ref><ref name=MEMCh2>{{Citation\n| url   = http://www.memoriachilena.cl/602/w3-printer-94644.html\n| title = Lugares estrat\u00e9gicos\n| work  = Memoria chilena\n| language =Spanish\n| accessdate =December 30, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\nWith Spain and Great Britain at war again in the 1770s due to the [[American Revolutionary War]] local Spanish authorities in Chile received in 1779 the warning that a British fleet commanded by [[Edward Hughes (Royal Navy officer)|Edward Hughes]] was heading to Chilean coasts for an imminent attack. As concequence of this the [[Viceroyalty of Peru]] send economic aid to the garrisons at [[Valpara\u00edso]] and [[Valdivia]]. The suspected attack did however never happen. In late 1788 suspicion of British attack rose appeared once again, this time stemming from observations of ships off the coast of [[Coquimbo]].<ref name=Ossa2010>{{cite journal |last=Ossa Santa Cruz |first=Juan Luis |date=2010 |title=La criollizaci\u00f3n de un ej\u00e9rcito perif\u00e9rico, Chile, 1768\u20131810 |url=http://revistahistoria.uc.cl/estudios/2247/ |journal=[[Historia (history of the Americas journal)|Historia]] |volume=42 |issue=II |pages=413\u2013448 |access-date=January 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201133624/http://revistahistoria.uc.cl/estudios/2247/# |archive-date=February 1, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last=Bengoa |first=Jos\u00e9 |authorlink=Jos\u00e9 Bengoa|title=Historia de los antiguos mapuches del sur |url= |accessdate= |year=2003 |edition= |publisher=[[Catalonia (publisher)|Catalonia]] |location=Santiago |isbn=956-8303-02-2 |language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last=Guarda |first=Gabriel |authorlink=Gabriel Guarda |title=La econom\u00eda de Chile Austral antes de la colonizaci\u00f3n alemana |url= |accessdate= |year=1973 |edition= |publisher=[[Universidad Austral de Chile]] |location=[[Valdivia]] |isbn= |page=|language=Spanish}}\n*[[Gabriel Salazar|Salazar, Gabriel]] (1985). ''Labradores, Peones y Proletarios'' (in Spanish) (3rd ed.). [[LOM Ediciones]]. {{ISBN|956-282-269-9}}.\n*Salazar, Gabriel; [[Julio Pinto|Pinto, Julio]] (2002). ''Historia contempor\u00e1nea de Chile III. La econom\u00eda: mercados empresarios y trabajadores'' (in Spanish). [[LOM Ediciones]]. {{ISBN|956-282-172-2}}.\n*{{cite book |last=Valenzuela M\u00e1rquez |first=Jaime |editor-last1=Gaune |editor-first1=Rafael |editor-last2=Lara |editor-first2=Mart\u00edn |title=Historias de racismo y discriminaci\u00f3n en Chile |publisher= |date=2009 |pages= |chapter=Esclavos mapuches. Para una historia del secuestro y deportaci\u00f3n de ind\u00edgenas en la colonia|isbn=|language=Spanish}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Villalobos |first1=Sergio|authorlink1=Sergio Villalobos |last2=Silva |first2=Osvaldo|last3=Silva |first3=Fernando|last4=Estelle |first4=Patricio  |title=Historia de Chile |url= |edition=14th |accessdate= |year=1974 |publisher=Editorial Universitaria|location=[[Santiago, Chile|Santiago de Chile]] |isbn=956-11-1163-2 |language=Spanish}}\n\n{{Spanish America}}\n{{Chile topics}}\n\n[[Category:Captaincy General of Chile]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: continous->continuous", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colonial_Chile"}
